<HEAD>NAACP Drops Out of NY Times Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> said Friday it had pulled out of a suit against <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> that charged the newspaper's real estate advertisements promote racial discrimination by featuring white models. Director Dr. <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hooks </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> `` suspended its participation'' because the organization had not held direct negotiations with the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> prior to filing the suit, contrary to longstanding policy. The suit was filed Thursday in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disrict </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> by the New York Open Housing Center and four individuals, along with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> for the Advancement of Colored People. `` While other members of the coalition met with representatives of the Times, the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> was not represented and hence the Times' publisher, <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Ochs </PERSON> <PERSON> Sulzberger </PERSON>, was correct when he complained that the lawsuit was filed without any discussion with the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Hooks </PERSON> said in a news release Hooks said the failure to hold direct talks occurred `` through an adminstrative oversight.'' Hooks said the suit had not been dropped and a meeting with <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> officials would be sought. `` We regret any confusion that might have arisen over this matter and have taken steps internally to see that such an oversight does not occur again,'' <PERSON> Hooks </PERSON> said. On Thursday, the Times issued a statement maintaining that its advertising conforms with anti-discrimination laws and saying the complaint appeared at first reading to be `` without merit.'' The plaintiffs said photos and drawings that accompany real estate ads in the Times `` depict whites almost exclusively as potential residents, thus indicating a preference based on race.''
