<HEAD>A Chronology Of The Goetz Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in the Saturday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Goetz Sentencing, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a chronology of events in the <PERSON> Bernhard </PERSON> <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> case:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1984</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 DEC. 22 _ Gunman shoots four young <PERSON> black </PERSON> men on subway train and escapes. DEC. 31 _ <PERSON> Bernhard </PERSON> <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON>, 37, of <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, surrenders to state police in <LOCATION> Concord </LOCATION>, N.H.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1985</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 JAN. 3 _ <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> returns to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and is arraigned on charges of attempted murder and illegal weapons possession. JAN. 25 _ Grand jury indicts <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> for illegal weapons possession, rejecting charges of attempted murder. MARCH 27 _ Second grand jury hears new witnesses, including two of those wounded who had refused to testify to previous grand jury without grants of immunity. <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> indicted on four counts of attempted murder, one count of reckless endangerment, four counts of assault and illegal weapons charges. JAN. 16 _ Acting state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Crane </PERSON> drops attempted murder charges because he says grand jury was not properly instructed on laws of justification. JULY 8 _ The state's highest court, the <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, reinstates attempted murder charges. DEC. 12 _ Jury selection begins.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1987</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 APRIL 7 _ Jury selection completed, with half of those seated crime victims. APRIL 27 _ Trial opens with prosecutor calling <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> `` vicious, even sadistic'' in shooting the young men, while defense claims <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> `` gave the victims _ thugs _ what the law allows.'' JUNE 16 _ Jury acquits <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> of attempted murder but convicts him on one count of illegal gun possession. OCT. 19 _ <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> sentenced to six months in prison and five years' probation
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1988</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 JUNE 29 _ Appellate Division rules that six-month sentence for weapon possession is illegal because law mandates either one-year term or indeterminate sentence. Because of legal peculiarity, <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> would be eligible for release after serving two months of one-year term, but must complete four months of six-month term. NOV. 22 _ <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upholds <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON>'s conviction for gun possession and agrees that six-month sentence was wrong.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1989</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 JAN. 13 _ <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> resentenced to one year in jail and fined $ 5,000. He will be eligible for parole in 51 days.
</TEXT>
