<HEAD>Brief Sketches of Bernhard Goetz's Four Shooting Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Saturday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Goetz Sentencing, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are brief sketches of <PERSON> Bernhard </PERSON> <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON>'s four shooting victims, all of whom were 19 when <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> shot them on Dec. 22, 1984, with an unlicensed .38 - caliber <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON>, who was resentenced Friday to one year in jail for possessing the gun used in the shootings, has said he thought he was about to be mugged by the four as he rode the subway. The victims say they were only panhandling. Three of the victims, <PERSON> Darrell </PERSON> <PERSON> Cabey </PERSON>, <PERSON> Troy </PERSON> <PERSON> Canty </PERSON> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramseur </PERSON>, filed lawsuits totaling $ 63.5 million against <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> that were consolidated in state court in October. The lawsuit could not proceed unless <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> was sentenced, ending his criminal trial, according to <PERSON> Cabey </PERSON> attorney <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Kunstler </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ <PERSON> Darrell </PERSON> <PERSON> Cabey </PERSON> was the most seriously injured of <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON>'s victims; he was paralyzed from the waist down and suffered brain damage During <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON>'s 1987 trial, a neurologist, <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Macaluso </PERSON>, testified that <PERSON> Cabey </PERSON> fell into a coma and `` a persistent vegetative state'' that lasted six weeks while hospitalized. `` He sits and watches TV. His mother struggles to make a life for him,'' <PERSON> Kunstler </PERSON> said Friday. <PERSON> Kunstler </PERSON> initially opposed the consolidation of the three lawsuits filed against <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> because he said the other two plaintiffs are notorious felons and <PERSON> Cabey </PERSON> would be prejudiced by association with them.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramseur </PERSON> was wounded in his left arm and chest He is serving an eight-year sentence at Coxsackie Correctional facility for raping and robbing a woman. During the trial, he said <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> attorney <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Slotnick </PERSON> tried to `` kill my credibility'' during courtroom questioning. `` I'm not the defendant. I was the victim of that crime,'' <PERSON> Ramseur </PERSON> said. After he refused to testify, he was taken from the court, held in contempt and his testimony was stricken from the record. `` I do n't feel that if I testified it would have made any difference,'' <PERSON> Ramseur </PERSON> said after the trial. <PERSON> Ramseur </PERSON> has said all along that he and <PERSON> Cabey </PERSON> were sitting when <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> started shooting. He said he thought the jury should have found <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> guilty of attempted murder and assault.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> claimed his Fifth Amendment right against self-incrimination 21 times after being sworn in during <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON>'s He was threatened with contempt. He was denied immunity from prosecution if he testified. He served time at <LOCATION> Rikers </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> city jail for violating parole for a necklace snatching. The state <ORGANIZATION> Correctional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> was paroled in October.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ <PERSON> Troy </PERSON> <PERSON> Canty </PERSON> is a self-described former drug addict and ninth-grade dropout who calmly handled tough questioning by <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> attorney <PERSON> Slotnick </PERSON> On the stand, <PERSON> Canty </PERSON> wore a suit and tie and was well groomed. <PERSON> Slotnick </PERSON> placed a large photograph near Canty of him in sneakers and a jacket glaring at a photographer. <PERSON> Canty </PERSON> acknowledged his past: often in trouble in school, attacking a teacher, being sent to a psychiatric day school for `` hostile and assaultive'' behavior.'' He said he learned how to break into video machines when he was 14 or 15 and shoplifted in department stores. He started smoking marijuana at 13 or 14. By the time he met <PERSON> Goetz </PERSON> on the subway, he said, he was using crack twice a day and had been arrested and convicted on theft charges. He testified he was no longer a drug addict and hoped to enter a cook training course.
</TEXT>
