<FIRST>r a PM-ScienceFront     01-13 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Science Front,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Science Front</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Similar version in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Among developments on the science front:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MEDICINE-BLACKS</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New research indicates blacks have less access to medical care than whites. According to a 1986 nationwide telephone survey, one in 11 blacks reported not seeing a doctor for economic reasons, compared with one in 20 whites. And blacks who did go to a doctor may not have been treated as well as whites, the study said. The report, which appears in today's Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, also said blacks were less likely to have health insurance. Another study in the Journal reviewed 50 medical studies of trials of new drugs published from 1984-1986 and found that blacks were included in less than two-thirds of them. A third study looked at racial inequities in use of medical procedures for heart-disease patients in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, and found that whites were 1.38 times more likely to undergo angiography, a technique for taking X-rays of the heart, and 2.26 times more likely to undergo bypass operations.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>OSTEOPOROSIS</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists say a new treatment for osteoporosis has proved successful in reversing the bone loss that afflicts an estimated 5 million Americans. A five-year clinical test reveals that use of a new slow-release form of sodium fluoride _ long used by dentists to strengthen teeth _ when given with calcium citrate can reverse the effects of osteoporosis by increasing bone mass, researchers at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday. Spinal osteoporosis, a gradual loss of a kind of bone found primarily in the spine, commonly affects elderly, postmenopausal women and results in shortened stature, curvature of the back and a protruding abdomen that can cause back pain and discomfort in the digestive system.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ULCERS</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new ulcer drug that is still being tested is superior to one of the mainstays of ulcer treatment because it promotes healing and relieves symptoms more quickly, according to a new study. The study found the new drug, known as omeprazole, worked better in patients with stomach ulcers than Zantac, one of two widely used treatments for ulcers. Both work by blocking the body's secretion of hydrochloric acid. After one month of treatment, ulcers had healed in 80 percent of those getting omeprazole and 59 percent receiving Zantac. After two months, 96 percent of the omeprazole patients and 85 percent of the Zantac patients had healed. The results were published in Thursday's issue of the New England Journal of Medicine.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MEASLES</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> recommends two significant changes in the routine for measles vaccinations. _ Infants under 15 months old, in areas where recurrent measles is a problem, should get two measles shots instead of one _ a shot of measles vaccine alone at 9 months, and a second dose at 15 months of the commonly used measless-mumps-rubella vaccine. _ In schools with measles outbreaks _ and in nearby schools where the disease might spread _ all students whose measles shots came before 1980 should be re-vaccinated, along with their siblings. Measles specialists have discovered two major outbreak patterns in recent years: outbreaks among infants under the 15-month vaccination age and outbreaks among school-age children who have been vaccinated but still got measles anyway. As much as 10 percent of all vaccinations do n't provide the intended protection.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>HERPES</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Studies show that acyclovir, an antiviral drug, can reduce or eliminate recurrent outbreaks of genital herpes even when taken for more than a year, a researcher reported. Dr. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, a specialist in obstetrics and gynecology, said Thursday that a study involving 261 patients with active herpes infections showed that outbreaks of the disease were virtually eliminated for about half of those taking acyclovir twice daily. The others who took the drug experienced milder, shorter outbreaks. Although earlier studies showed that acyclovir was effective temporarily against herpes, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said the trial was the first to demonstrate that the antiviral drug is effective over many months. A report on the study was published this month in the journal Obstetrics and Gynecology.
</TEXT>
