<HEAD>Belgian Soldier Tells Police Killings Were Acts Of Revenge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Belgian soldier assigned to his country's <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> embassy surrendered to police Thursday, saying he had killed two people here as revenge after breaking up with his male lover, authorities said. <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Den </PERSON> <PERSON> Borre </PERSON>, 25, surrendered after making several calls to police, challenging them to `` come and find me.'' He was booked into Broward County Jail without bond on two counts of first-degree murder. He told the officer who arrested him early Thursday that he'd killed two people and was planning another murder as revenge against the lover he'd just broken up with, the <LOCATION> Broward </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff's office said in a `` He had a lover's quarrel with his boyfriend up -LRB- in -RRB- the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> area,'' sheriff's Sgt. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Carney </PERSON> told reporters. `` He came down here, he was emotionally upset about that.'' Police statements said <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Den </PERSON> <PERSON> Borre </PERSON> arrived in south <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> Jan. 4 and wandered around the <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION> beach area visiting gay hangouts. `` And he meets these people at local clubs, goes down on the beach with them and at some point decides that he's going to shoot and kill them,'' <PERSON> Carney </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Egan </PERSON>, a 36-year-old airline reservation clerk from <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION>, was found shot in the head Jan. 8. Less than 24 hours later, the body of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> cab driver <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Simons </PERSON>, 52, was found, similarly killed. <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION> police said both victims were homosexuals. Because <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Den </PERSON> <PERSON> Borre </PERSON> is a diplomatic employee, there is some question about his status before the law. Officials said the <ORGANIZATION> Belgian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> had been told of the charges against him and was cooperating in the investigation.
</TEXT>
