<HEAD>Recording Industry's Newest Star Revives Singer-Songwriter Tradition</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>^With PM-Grammys, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Tracy </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> seems of another time, a time when <PERSON> Dylan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Odetta </PERSON>, <PERSON> Seeger </PERSON> and <PERSON> Guthrie </PERSON> celebrated freedom and the spirit of man, and defied brutality and repression with their songs and anthems. <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>, whose self-titled debut album has been nominated for six Grammys, is of this age and her songs take a hard, cold look at poverty, racism, inequality and human relations. She is uncompromising, tough and compassionate. `` I think people look at the world in many different ways and choose to see what they like,'' she said in an interview last year with <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>. `` I think lots of people ignore some of the harder issues, the more unpleasant things. I do n't think I harp on them.'' Her LP opens with `` Talkin' Bout a Revolution,'' a song that tells of `` standing in the welfare lines Crying at the doorsteps of those armies of salvation Wasting time in the unemployment lines Sitting around waiting for a promotion Poor people gon na rise up And get their share Poor people gon na rise up And take what's theirs.'' Until `` <PERSON> Tracy </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>'' hit record stores last April, the 24-year-old poet-singer-songwriter-folksinger was one of the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> area's best kept secrets. As an anthrolopolgy major at <ORGANIZATION> Tufts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Medford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, she performed in coffee houses and clubs, and was a local hit. The LP, with its range from folk to pop ballad to reggae, enchanted millions more. It has sold over 4 million copies and has been nominated for album of the year and best contemporary folk recording. The single, `` Fast Car,'' has been nominated for best song and record of the year, and <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> herself is up for best new artist and best female pop vocalist. `` Fast Car'' was a No. 1 hit and tells of a high school dropout who works to supports her alcoholic father and who wants to escape it all with her unemployed boyfriend: `` You got a fast car And I got a plan to get us out of here I been working at the convenience store Managed to save just a little bit of money We wo n't have to drive too far Just ` cross the border and into the city You and I can both get jobs And finally see what it means to be living. <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>'s rich contralto with its melancholic underpinnings is an instrument by itself and highly effective on `` Behind the Wall,'' a song about a battered woman. She sings a capella of the harsh realties of the domestic fight: `` Last night I heard the screaming - Then a silence that chilled my soul'' _ and slams the police for doing nothing. She grew up in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> and has been singing since she was a child. She was in a <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> boarding school when singer-songwriters had been put out to pasture by synthesizer philistines. <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> did n't turn on her radio, but many of her classmates listened to folk music and played guitar. In college, one of her classmates was <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Koppelman </PERSON>, whose father, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON>, is a leader in the music publishing business. This gave her the wedge she needed to gain entry to the recording world. <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>, whose musical roots can be traced to <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Armatrading </PERSON>, <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> and <PERSON> Joni </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, was part of a new wave of singer-songwriters in the late 1980s, especially women such as <PERSON> Toni </PERSON> <PERSON> Childs </PERSON>, <PERSON> Marti </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, <PERSON> Melissa </PERSON> <PERSON> Etheridge </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michelle </PERSON> <PERSON> Shocked </PERSON>.
