<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: US Scores Last-Minute Successes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With only a week to go, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration is managing to eke out a few foreign policy successes before turning leadership in world affairs over to President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his deputies. The withdrawal of 450 Cuban soldiers from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> this week marks the beginning of the end of a 14-year presence in the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> country. The pullout is part of a deal arranged by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that will bring independence to <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, now under South African control. <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON>, the assistant secretary of state for African affairs, worked eight difficult years for a settlement, continuing efforts that began early in the <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> administration. The Cuban exodus does not end the war in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. The Marxist government, armed by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, is still fighting the rebel Union for the Total Independence of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>, which has been supported by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. But the war is likely to be less intense, and <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> will get the independence <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> was unwilling to grant despite worldwide condemnation. In <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, the Soviets have again started to withdraw their troops despite threats to stall until a political settlement is worked out with U.S.-armed rebels. Transports carried some units out by air this week, while others streamed northward from the Soviet garrison in the capital city of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. By Feb. 15, the last of the 50,000 Soviet troops are supposed to be gone. Here, too, the departure of a foreign army does not mean peace is settling in. But the fighting may slacken. Rebels armed by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> have government forces on the run. Without Soviet backing, however, President <PERSON> Najibullah </PERSON> and his army could collapse without much of a struggle. Soviet troops have been in the country since December 1979. Their ouster was a main foreign policy goal of the <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> and then the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. Success came partly as a result of massive Soviet losses and the kind of anguish at home that Americans suffered during the <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> war. But the advent of <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in April 1985 and the smoother relationship he worked out with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had a lot to do with it. Superpower cooperation also helped bring about the African settlement and the ongoing Vietnamese troop withdrawal from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, although it did not crack the <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> conflict or have an impact on the wars in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. In the meantime, the outgoing administration is defying tradition by not just fading away. Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> has purchased his tickets for flying home to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> right after the inaugural next Friday. But a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> jet is waiting for him to board at <ORGANIZATION> Andrews </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Base this weekend. The idea is to fly to <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> and celebrate the end of a 27-month human rights conference, hold a 32nd and final meeting with Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> and make preparations for East-West arms control talks. Those negotiations will seek the reduction of troops all across the European landscape. The idea is to ease tensions between the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact. To get those talks going, the Soviets met <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> demands for the release of more than 600 political prisoners, the reunification of more than 100 families and stepped-up emigration of Jews, ethnic Germans and Armenians. The <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> trip is on hold, though, pending resolution of a dispute between <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> over how much Turkish territory across from <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> will be included in the reduction talks.
