<HEAD>Hawaii Convention For Troubled System Stirs Protests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, an arm of the financially beleaguered Farm Credit System, says it makes sense to send nearly 200 of its representatives to <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> later this month for a midwinter convention. Protests have been raised by a grassroots unit in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, which tried unsuccessfully to get the council's <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, district to reduce its number of delegates to the meeting. The Fargo board objected to sending a 14-member district delegation, plus some staff people, to the Jan. 24 meeting scheduled at the Sheraton-Waikiki Hotel. After the one-day council meeting, most of the delegates will attend the annual convention of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperatives </ORGANIZATION> on Jan. 25-26. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>'s national office in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said the council is an affiliate of the <ORGANIZATION> NCFC </ORGANIZATION>, which will send about 800 delegates to <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>, compared with the council's 175 The council handles lobbying activities for the cooperative Farm Credit System, which includes nationwide networks of federal land banks, production credit associations, bank for cooperatives and the federal intermediate credit bank. Overall, the system has a loan portfolio of more than $ 50 billion. As a result of a continuing financial crisis and huge losses, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> late in 1987 drew up a bailout plan that could pour as much as $ 4 billion into the ailing system. <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON> said Thursday in a telephone interview that the <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> convention site was selected in 1983 by the <ORGANIZATION> NCFC </ORGANIZATION> and that the council had studied the situation for almost a year before deciding to go to <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> or hold its own annual meeting somewhere else and apart from the <ORGANIZATION> NCFC </ORGANIZATION>. Although there was some agonizing over the potential public relations harm of going to <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON> said that a cost analysis showed it was good business to join <ORGANIZATION> NCFC </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON> said other sites were studied, including <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, and cities in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. Air travel to <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> will be `` a little bit higher for a larger number of people'' than to mainland cities, he said. But those additional costs will be offset by other things, such as holding a joint reception and sharing other functions with the <ORGANIZATION> NCFC </ORGANIZATION>. `` So we decided to do it, knowing that there could be some criticism about it,'' <PERSON> Terrell </PERSON> said. Rep. <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dorgan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.D. </LOCATION>, called the decision to send Farm Credit System officials to <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> `` a foolish mistake'' in the wake of the $ 4 billion bailout passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` We did n't bail them out to send them to <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Dorgan </PERSON> said. `` We bailed them out to help family farmers.'' <PERSON> Dorgan </PERSON>, in response to an <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> query, said the Farm Credit System has `` done a pretty good job under some rough circumstances, but this is the kind of foolishness that shows a lack of sensitivity to how things look to the folks out there in the country who are paying bills.'' He added: `` There are plenty of empty hotels in the farm belt that would love to host a meeting of the Farm Credit folks. There might be less sun, and also less heat for the <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Flue-cured tobacco farmers and buyers each will be assessed 1.12 cents per pound for the 1989 crop, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said. The total of 2.24 cents covers a no-net cost assessment of 2 cents per pound and 0.24 cents to help cover the federal budget deficit. The 1989 total assessment will be down slightly from last year's total of 2.26 cents per pound. Department officials said Thursday they consulted with the Flue-cured <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stabilization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the producer-owned association that handles the support program, before determining the 1989 assessment. The budget deficit assessment will be imposed according to the Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1987, which calls for a reduction in the level of price support by 1.4 percent or, alternatively, an assessment on producers to achieve and equal reduction in spending. Officials said the 1989 price support for flue-cured tobacco will remain at $ 1.468 per pound as announced on Dec. 15 for this year's crop
