<HEAD>Antiviral Drug Effective Against Herpes, Researcher Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Studies at five medical centers have found that acyclovir, an antiviral drug, can reduce or eliminate recurrent outbreaks of genital herpes. Dr. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, a specialist in obstetrics and gynecology at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Stony </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brook </LOCATION>, said a double-blind study involving 261 patients with active herpes infections showed outbreaks of the disease were virtually eliminated for about half of those taking acyclovir twice daily. `` These were all patients who before had had about one recurrence of herpes a month'' and had been infected for more than a year, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said Thursday in a telephone interview. Genital herpes is caused by a virus that generally is spread through sexual contact in which one partner has open lesions of the disease.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Suggests Review of Tax Laws to Guard Against Abuses</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> says he would not advocate government action to curtail corporate takeovers but suggested a review of tax laws might be needed to guard against abuses. `` I am not in favor of the government picking winners and losers,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said at a news conference Thursday to announce his final Cabinet choices. Asked whether he planned action to put the brakes on increasing number of takeovers, many through so-called leveraged buyouts, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` You are talking to one who would as much as possible rely on market forces.'' But he added, that `` if there are abuses of our tax laws, ... the whole tax law will be reviewed to see how they can be eliminated.''
