<NOTE>National League Of Cities Survey Says Drugs And Housing Problems</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Worse
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials from the nation's cities say drugs and housing problems worsened in urban America last year, and the shortage of affordable housing is the top hindrance to local economic growth. The National League of Cities, releasing the findings Thursday of its annual survey of local officials, criticized the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration for major reductions in housing aid and for proposing to end local assistance to fight drugs. The league, which represents large and small municipalities across the country, surveyed 690 officials in 473 communities last month. Two-thirds of the town officials reported local drug problems had worsened in 1988, and crime was described as worsening by 45 percent.
