<DATELINE>CHIPPEWA FALLS, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 They held an election and no voters came. The two people who requested the referendum held Wednesday never arrived, as planned. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> and <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Schunk </PERSON> live on property within a 200-acre parcel annexed in December to the neighboring city of <LOCATION> Eau </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Claire </LOCATION>. An annexation can be vetoed by residents of the property, and that's what the Schunks did by not voting Polls at <PERSON> Hallie </PERSON> town hall opened at 9 a.m. and stayed open for 11 hours on the referendum question of whether the land ought to remain attached to <ORGANIZATION> Eau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Claire </ORGANIZATION>. The Schunks are the only residents of the tract. Town Attorney <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Raihle </PERSON> declared the election outcome a 0-0 tie. Under state law, the tie nullified the annexation, <PERSON> Raihle </PERSON> said. In an ordinary election, <PERSON> Hallie </PERSON> is a suburb of 4,500 eligible voters. The 200-acre parcel includes vacant lots, a few businesses and the Hallie Golf Course. The nullification of the annexation through the non-vote saves the town from taking <PERSON> Eau </PERSON> <PERSON> Claire </PERSON> to court, <PERSON> Raihle </PERSON> said, because some non-resident property owners would have insisted on suing. The referendum cost the town about $ 125, said Town Clerk <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Sippel </PERSON>.
