<HEAD>Head Of Government Inquiry Into Aboriginal Deaths Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANBERRA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The head of a government probe on the deaths of 104 aborigines in police custody has resigned, and indigenous activists today called the decision a devastating blow to the inquiry. Prime Minister <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawke </PERSON> said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Muirhead </PERSON>, federal court judge since 1977, resigned late Thursday to become administrator of the Northern Territory. Aboriginal groups called the decision a blow to their cause and expressed concern that the inquiry, set up in 1987 to investigate 44 aboriginal deaths in police custody since 1980, could be downgraded. Since the inquiry began, the number of aboriginal deaths in police custody has grown to 104, and <PERSON> Muirhead </PERSON> had said the increased number would extend his work _ expected to be completed last month _ two years minimum. Aboriginal activists have charged police brutality as the cause. An interim report issued last month recommended aboriginal recruits replace white police officers suspected of racism and that drunkenness be abolished as a crime for aborigines. Most aborigines have died in police cells by hanging after being picked up on charges of being drunk and disorderly. <PERSON> Hawke </PERSON> said <PERSON> Muirhead </PERSON>, who also was the judge in the <PERSON> Lindy </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamberlain </PERSON> trial, would continue in his job until April. The Chamberlain trial was the basis for the recent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> movie starring Meryl Streep entitled `` A Cry in the Dark.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> to </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defend </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>, which represents many of the families of aborigines who have died in custody, urged the federal government ensure that justice is not denied the country's indigenous population following <PERSON> Muirhead </PERSON>'s resignation Aborigines, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s original inhabitants, number about 160,000, or 1 percent of the 16 million population. Government figures statistics show aborigines are socially and economically deprived. Aboriginal activists declared last year's Bicentennial marking European settlement a year of mourning. <PERSON> Muirhead </PERSON>, 63, said aborigines should not fear the probe will wind down. `` I think the commission is well established,'' he said. No replacement was immediately named.
