<FIRST>r a PM-CDC--Measles     01-13 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CDC--Measles,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>CDC Recommends Changes In Vaccinations For Measles, Which Isn't Going
Away</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A decade after predicting measles was on the verge of eradication, federal health officials have proposed two new steps to try to wipe out the disease. The recommendations, issued Thursday by the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>, could mean an extra measles shot for thousands of infants and older children. According to the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>, the major outbreaks of measles in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in recent years have occurred among infants under the 15-month vaccination age and among school-age children who have been vaccinated but got measles anyway. As many as 10 percent of all vaccinations fail to provide the intended protection. To try to stop the outbreaks, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Immunization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Practices </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> has recommended: _ Infants younger than 15 months, in areas where recurrent measles is a problem, should get two measles shots instead of one _ a shot of measles vaccine alone at 9 months, and a second dose at 15 months in the commonly used measles-mumps-rubella vaccine _ In schools experiencing outbreaks and in nearby schools where the disease might spread, all students whose measles shots came before 1980 should be revaccinated, along with their siblings That 1980 cutoff was chosen because vaccinations before then may not have been as effective either because the vaccine subsequently was improved or because the vaccinations came earlier in life according to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy at the time, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. In the late 1970s, <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> measles specialists believed the once common childhood disease could be eradicated by fall 1982. But that goal was not met; from 1983 to 1988, between 1,497 and 6,282 measles cases have been reported in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> each year. Dr. <PERSON> Sonja </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutchins </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> measles specialist, could not predict how many children would be affected by the new recommendations, adding, `` We're in the process of analyzing that now.'' The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s recommendations are not binding on local health and education officials, but are widely recognized as health policy in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Local health officials will be responsible for monitoring measles in their communities and spreading the word about the new recommendations, Ms. <PERSON> Hutchins </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s immunization committee is recommending the two-dose routine for infants in any county that has had five preschool measles cases in each of the previous five years, and is urging revaccination of certain students at any high school or college where an outbreak is taking place or might spread from a nearby school. About one in 10 counties reported at least one measles case in 1987. More than 800 cases occurred in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> alone, another 469 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, 452 in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and 318 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. The nation's measles-eradication strategy, which stresses vaccination of infants, surveillance for measles and aggressive outbreak control, is unchanged, Ms. <PERSON> Hutchins </PERSON> said. `` These three elements are still important,'' she said. `` These two major recommendations are modifications to the current strategy.'' The two modifications come with alternatives, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. In affected areas where a two-dose infant schedule is n't possible, vaccination should come at 12 months, not 15, the agency said And if a school fighting a measles outbreak ca n't revaccinate all students whose shots came before 1980, it should at least target students vaccinated before the age of 15 months.
</TEXT>
