<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>British, German Warplanes Collide, Two Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with more background on military crashes
in West Germany and upcoming government report on the problem. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BREMEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A British Tornado warplane flew into a group of eight West German jet fighters today and collided with two of them, killing the two British crewmen and injuring a German pilot, officials said. Several houses were slightly damaged on the edge of the northern village of <LOCATION> Wiesmoor </LOCATION> by debris from the Tornado but there were no civilian casualties, local police said. The Tornado crashed into a field just outside Wiesmoor, while one German plane came down a few miles away, the defense spokesman said. The other plane involved in the crash managed to land safely, he said. The pilot of the German jet that crashed was injured, he said. The accident came amid growing complaints among the West German public about the dangers to civilians from <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> training flights over this densely populated country. More than 100 people were killed in military-related plane crashes last year in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. A spokesman at the West German <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> said the British plane flew into a group of eight German Alfajet fighters preparing to land at <LOCATION> Wittmund </LOCATION> air base near <LOCATION> Wiesmoor </LOCATION>, 50 miles northwest of the port city of <LOCATION> Bremen </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, who asked not to be identified by name, said the Tornado plane collided with two of the Alfajets. Earlier reports indicated the British plane crashed with only one German fighter. A spokesman at the British forces headquarters in <LOCATION> Rheindahlen </LOCATION> confirmed the Tornado had crashed after the collision, killing the two-man British crew. `` We can confirm that a <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Tornado jet from No. 14 Squadron at the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> base <LOCATION> Brueggen </LOCATION> crashed near the village of <LOCATION> Wiesmoor </LOCATION>, killing the pilot and the navigator,'' the spokesman said. <LOCATION> Brueggen </LOCATION> is near the West German border with the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, 210 miles south of the crash site. The spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the Tornado was on a routine training mission when it crashed. A Wiesmoor police spokesman said the injured German pilot had been taken to a nearby hospital. It was not immediately clear whether the pilot sustained his injuries while ejecting from the airplane. Identities of the British crew killed in the crash `` will not be released pending notification of next of kin,'' the British forces spokesman said. He said a team of experts was traveling to the scene to investigate the crash. In the worst military crash in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> last year, 70 people died after three <LOCATION> Italian </LOCATION> air force stunt jets collided during an air show at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> base in <LOCATION> Ramstein </LOCATION> that was attended by thousands of people. The last major <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> plane crash occurred on Dec. 8, when a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> A-10 Thunderbolt slammed into a residential neighborhood in the city of <LOCATION> Remscheid </LOCATION>, killing the pilot and five people on the ground. The West German <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> is expected next week to submit a report on ways to reduce military aircraft training flights.
