<HEAD>Human Rights Accord Accepted With New East Bloc Freedoms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: New throut to ADD diplomats' views on significance of agreement,
CLARIFY that final accord possible this week. No pickup. ^By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A conference of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and Western nations today informally accepted a landmark accord on human rights and security, diplomats said. The pact calls for freedom of travel and religion in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc. However, a Greek-Turkish dispute still blocked a final agreement among the 35 nations that is to include a mandate for new European talks on conventional weapons, said the diplomats, who spoke on condition of anonymity. If the deadlock is broken, a final pact could be signed on Saturday, they said. The disagreement between <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> over a Turkish port in the eastern <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> has prevented negotiators from the 16 <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> and seven <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact nations from approving the new East-West talks on reducing conventional troops and weapons across <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Twelve non-aligned nations are also attending the conference. Agreement on the human rights and security accord came after more than two years of tough East-West bargaining at the <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> review conference, which opened in November 1986. A copy of the accord, obtained by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, showed landmark agreements on the freedom of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc citizens to travel, practice religion and monitor their countries' compliance with human rights. Western diplomats called the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> document a milestone. Its key test, however, will be whether the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and its allies actually stick to the new commitments. The pact `` refined and defined the humanitarian undertakings in far greater detail than ever possible before,'' said <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> envoy <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauer </PERSON>. He and other Western diplomats said reforms in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> played a major role in securing the agreement. The diplomats also said the human rights provisions contained in the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> document are more specific than any others since the <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> process began with the signing of the <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> Final Act in 1975. The document also provides a mechanism by which any two of the signatories can raise human rights issues. Western diplomats described that agreement as a major achievement. The conference is scheduled to wind up next week with a three-day closing ceremony attended by foreign ministers from all the signatories of the 1975 <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> Final Act: the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and all European nations except <LOCATION> Albania </LOCATION>. But that ceremony was put in jeopardy today because of the failure to break the deadlock between <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. If the impasse is broken, a final document could be accepted in a public meeting on Saturday, diplomats said. <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> agreed with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> that the eastern <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> port of <LOCATION> Mersin </LOCATION>, which is close to Syrian border, should be excluded from the new East-West arms talks. But <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> insists the port must be considered. It says <LOCATION> Mersin </LOCATION> is a key port for shipping supplies to northern <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, which is controlled by <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. The rest of the island is controlled by <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. Greek Ambassador <PERSON> Evangelos </PERSON> <PERSON> Frangoulis </PERSON> denied at a news conference today that <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> raised its objections at the last minute. He said <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> would be happy to put aside the issue until the <LOCATION> East-West </LOCATION> arms talks open, probably in March. Diplomats say, however, that <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> will not accept this compromise. In an attempt to break the deadlock, the 35-nation conference worked into the night Thursday. A draft document presented on behalf of the non-aligned nations early today was informally accepted by caucuses of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact and the 12 nations of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, diplomats said. The only outstanding human rights issue remained <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s acceptance of a controversial human rights conference in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in 1991 <PERSON> Bauer </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> envoy, said this morning he expected firm assurances from the Soviets during the day that they would permit a <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> couple waiting for 10 years for exit visas to emigrate. He indicated that <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> would then agree to the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> conference.
