<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A prosecutor today said he has opened a criminal investigation into the Imhausen-Chemie company, which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> claims helped build a chemical weapons plant in <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Werner </PERSON> <PERSON> Botz </PERSON>, chief prosecutor in <LOCATION> Offenburg </LOCATION>, said he opened the probe after reading a report on the dispute in this week's Stern magazine. <PERSON> Stern </PERSON>, a nationwide news magazine known for its investigative reporting, said Imhausen-Chemie was involved in the Libyan plant, along with I.B.I. Engineering of <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> and the Hamburg-based <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> <PERSON> Tsao </PERSON> medical material company. Imhausen-Chemie has denied any connection to the plant in <LOCATION> Rabta </LOCATION>, 60 miles outside <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION>. News reports and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government sources have said Imhausen-Chemie provided much of the technical equipment for the facility, which <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said was built to manufacture poison gas. <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> said the plant will produce pharmaceuticals. <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Frey </PERSON>, a spokesman for the prosecutor's office in <LOCATION> Karlsruhe </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Offenburg </LOCATION>, said the possible charge being investigated is `` a violation of the export control law.'' He said he had no other information about the probe. Imhausen-Chemie, I.B.I. and <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> <PERSON> Tsao </PERSON> have been named by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials in their accusations that West German companies aided <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> in building the plant. Federal officials have audited Imhausen-Chemie and said they could find no evidence of wrongdoing on the part of the Lahr-based company. Federal officials also cleared <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> <PERSON> Tsao </PERSON> of suspicions of wrongdoing but said investigators were examining records seized from I.B.I., which is no longer in business. TV and magazine reports have shown bank documents and other records said to establish Libyan financial links with Imhausen-Chemie and I.B.I. Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> said Thursday authorities uncovered new documents implicating West German companies in deliveries of equipment for the plant. His spokesman, <PERSON> Friedhelm </PERSON> <PERSON> Ost </PERSON>, today conceded that <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> officials first learned of `` indications'' in October that West German companies were involved with the plant. <PERSON> Ost </PERSON> was asked about reports alleging <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> officials have known for as long as two years that Imhausen-Chemie and other West German companies may have been involved in the project. He said intelligence sources mentioned the possibility of West German involvement in October but contended they had no evidence then or now that can be used for legal action against any West German companies. Today's announcement followed the arrest of a Belgian shipping agent linked to the case and confirmation Thursday by <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> ambassador that West German companies assisted in the project. The ambassador, <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Treiki </PERSON>, told <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> that <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> `` did help us, not only in this plant, in other plants also.'' Federal officials said this week that Belgian authorities had arrested and charged <PERSON> Jozef </PERSON> <PERSON> Gedopt </PERSON>, director-general of <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Link </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> NV </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Antwerp </LOCATION>, with forging shipping documents for goods delivered to <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> ZDF </ORGANIZATION> television network said <PERSON> Gedopt </PERSON>'s company allegedly used a Cyprus-registered freighter to deliver West German equipment to <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> in February 1986 after forging destination papers. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday that Libyan officials contacted West German companies for clean-up help after a dangerous chemical spill in August at the facility. Both <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> quoted unidentified officials as saying the evidence included extensive interceptions of telephone conversations between the Libyans and their suppliers.
