<HEAD>Investigators Report Wiring OK in Engines in Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Investigators have determined that the engines of a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 that crashed Sunday north of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> were correctly wired, a newspaper said. The report, if true, would rule out a possible cause of the disaster. Meanwhile, the plane's engines were crated for shipment today to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, where the manufacturer will search for clues to the cause of the crash. The British <ORGANIZATION> Midland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> jet, flying from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION>, crashed into a roadside embankment while attempting an emergency landing at an airport 100 miles north of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The disaster killed 44 people and injured 82. Investigators are now trying to solve a major mystery in the crash: why the plane's right engine shut down when the left engine was on fire. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> authorities earlier this week ordered checks on the wiring of similar aircraft engines. That move prompted speculation that a faulty alarm system may have misled the British <ORGANIZATION> Midland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> crew into shutting down the wrong engine, causing the crash. The pilot had reported his right engine on fire, but evidence of a fire was found afterward only in the left engine. The Times of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> said investigators were `` as certain as can be'' that the engines were correctly wired after checks on similar engines ended Thursday. Investigators are still no nearer to discovering the cause of the engine problems and do not know if the cockpit misinterpreted instruments in the control panel, the paper said. The CFM56 engines, jointly made by <ORGANIZATION> U.S.-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> SNECMA </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> France </L