<HEAD>Parliament Accepts Resignations Of Leadership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Montenegrin Parliament today accepted the resignations of the republic's six-man presidency. The leaders quit following protests over the region's failing economy. <LOCATION> Montenegro </LOCATION>'s representative in the federal presidency also stepped down. The resignations marked the first time the entire state and <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leaderships of one of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s six republics had stepped down. The ouster of the ruling elite came after more than 120,000 people demonstrated in <LOCATION> Titograd </LOCATION>, the region's capital, earlier this week and demanded new leadership because of the disastrous state of the economy. <LOCATION> Montenegro </LOCATION>'s government resigned after mass protests in October. `` The current mass dissatisfaction among the workers, students and young people is due to a large extent to the difficulties faced by the country as a whole,'' said parliament's vice president, <PERSON> Bozidar </PERSON> <PERSON> Tadic </PERSON>, in a speech broadcast live on national television. The central committee of <LOCATION> Montenegro </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday accepted the resignation of its ruling Presidium and named interim leadership to prepare for an extraordinary party congress. The parliament, which decided that the republic's presidency will act as a caretaker until new elections are held, also accepted the resignation of its speaker, <PERSON> Velisav </PERSON> <PERSON> Vuksanovic </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Montenegro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s smallest republic and one of its poorest, has been particularly hard hit by the country's economic problems and a decline in living standards. The nation faces a $ 21 billion foreign debt and in 1988 alone inflation ran at 250 percent. The average monthly salary in <LOCATION> Montenegro </LOCATION> is the equivalent of about $ 80. Unemployment in the region soared after closure of a number of unprofitable enterprises previously subsidized by the federal government.
