<SECOND>AM-Investment Fund Loss,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>W.Va. Governor Says `2 Sets of Books' Contributed to Investment Fund
Loss</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.V. GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Contradictory bookkeeping procedures and a desire to boost commissions within the treasurer's office contributed to losses of $ 279 million in the state's investment fund, Gov. Arch <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, who leaves office Monday, announced the findings of a private audit of the fund Thursday. It was the Republican's first public comment on the investment fund loss since it became public after the Nov. 8 election, in which <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> was defeated by Democrat <PERSON> Gaston </PERSON> <PERSON> Caperton </PERSON>. State officials have n't said yet which state agencies and local governments will absorn the losses, so the effect of the missing money is not clear, said <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Farley </PERSON>, a Democrat. Even without taking into account the missing $ 279 million, the state has been experiencing financial problems so severe that income tax refunds were delayed up to five months in 1988. House of Delegates Speaker <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON>, a Democrat, said after the governor's announcement that it appeared the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investments </ORGANIZATION> was n't paying attention when the investment fund was losing money. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> chairs the board, whose other members are Treasurer <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Manchin </PERSON> and Auditor <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Gainer </PERSON>. The board has nominal control of the investment fund. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said at a news conference that <PERSON> Manchin </PERSON>'s office was making inflated and unrealistic interest payments to local governments, even when the losses were piling up, so the treasury could attract commissions. The consolidated fund's losses totaled $ 279 million through Nov. 30, said <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>. The audit by <ORGANIZATION> Touche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ross </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` ascertained that the treasurer's office kept two sets of books,'' said <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>. `` They kept one set of books to determine what they paid out in interest. Another set -LRB- was kept -RRB- as related to their transactions and they never reconciled the two methods.'' For example, the central investment pool in the consolidated investment fund paid out rates of 9 percent, 8.3 percent, and 7.8 percent respectively in April, May and June 1987, when the losses were severest and the fund had no earnings, the audit showed. `` You will find that the treasurer's office was paying out tremendously large sums of money that they were not earning,'' <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Manchin </PERSON>, however, was unhappy with the reference to `` two sets of books.'' `` I would like to believe that it was one accounting system which took care of profits and the losses. There was another accounting system which took care of the distributions. The distributions never have shown where the losses were,'' the treasurer said. Under the guidelines of the fund, created in 1978, the treasurer could go to an outside agency to handle investments or he could charge a commission on what investments he could gather from local governnments. The commissions `` were not monitored by the Legislature. They were a fund out of which the treasurer's office could do essentially what he wanted to do,'' said <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>. The fund generated from commissions was used to pay for day-to-day expenses in the treasurer's office. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said the investment office borrowed billions of dollars' worth of funds from brokerage houses to help buy the huge amounts of securities transactions that were being handled by the investment office The $ 1.7 billion fund saw sales of $ 80.5 billion in 1987. The audit showed that $ 27.2 billion was borrowed in 1986 and 1987, including $ 10.8 billion in April 1987, the month in which the largest loss was recorded. An addition, $ 4.3 billion was borrowed in 1988. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said much of the borrowing occurred without the knowledge of the Board of Investments.
