<HEAD>Retail Sales Surge In 1988 Despite Weak December Spending</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Retail sales grew in 1988 at their strongest pace in four years, the government reported Friday, but the year went out with a whimper of weak holiday sales at department stores and car dealerships. Sales totaled $ 1.61 trillion for the year, up 6.7 percent from 1987 and the largest annual increase since a 9.8 percent gain in 1984, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said. But despite rosy expectations for strong year-end sales by retailers and car dealers, December sales were up just 0.2 percent from the previous month to a seasonally adjusted $ 138 billion. December's gain was the slowest since a 0.3 drop in September that was followed by a revised 1.7 percent increase in October and a 0.9 percent rise in November. The figures are not adjusted to exclude the effects of rising prices. Economist <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, said that while the overall sales figure for 1988 turned out to be `` a lot better than we feared it was going to be after the stock market crash'' in October 1987, December's numbers were unexpectedly low. `` It suggests that we're entering 1989 with a lot less momentum than we thought we had,'' <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON> said. `` I would n't call it a worry yet, but it does suggest that the economy is going to be slowing down in 1989.'' <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Levy </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Levy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forecasts </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chappaqua </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, said the report shows consumers `` have moved toward caution'' after a period of more buoyant spending. The bond market rallied in early action Friday as traders read the sales figures as a sign of a slowing economy that would place less upward pressure on interest rates. However, some economists were skeptical about the implications of the report, saying December's weak numbers later might be revised upward and that they might not reflect strong sales late in the month, particularly of automobiles. `` All I know is that auto companies were well satisfied with what they saw and the general merchandisers were well satisfied,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dederick </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaber </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said that while retail sales were n't as strong as expected for December, spending still showed modest growth that should continue into the new year. While overall retail sales for the year were posting their best showing since 1984, the department store category rose by just 4.5 percent, the smallest annual gain since a 3.4 percent rise in the recession year of 1982. This sluggish performance was offset by a 9.5 percent rise in auto sales for the year, up sharply from a 1.8 percent increase in 1987. However, auto sales actually fell in December, dropping 0.3 percent from the previous month and posting the first decline since a 1.4 percent drop in September. Excluding autos, retail sales were up 0.3 percent in December, following a 0.6 percent rise in November. Retail spending is seen as a key barometer of economic health because it represents about one-third of the gross national product. The holiday season is particularly important because it can account for half of a general retailer's annual profits. Sales by general merchandisers reached $ 15.76 billion in December, up 0.3 percent from a month earlier. Other categories posting gains during December included furniture stores, service stations and bars and restaurants. Sales decreased at food, clothing and drug stores.
