<TEXT>
 A `` Friday the 13th'' computer virus struck personal computers in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> on Friday, wiping out program files and annoying businesses, a computer expert said. Hundreds of personal computer users found the virus was programmed to delete files on Friday the 13th, said <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON>, managing director of S and <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION>, a data recovery center in <LOCATION> Chesham </LOCATION>. The virus, which might be a new species, has been slowing down computers made by <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and compatible models, said <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON>, who also is chairman of an <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> personal computer users group. Telephone lines to the center were busy with calls for help from businesses and individuals whose computers were struck by the virus, he said. `` It has been frisky and hundreds of people, including a large firm with over 400 computers, have telephoned with their problems,'' he said. A spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Portsmouth </LOCATION>, who asked not to be identified, confirmed that the virus had wiped out files in personal computers made by <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> and compatible machines. He said he did n't know whether larger computers were affected In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, several computer-security experts said today they had not heard any reports the virus had crossed the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> said his company would try to figure out how the virus operates and then attempt to kill it. The identity of the hacker who devised the virus might never be known, he said. `` It is just a pesky nuisance and is causing a lot of problems today,'' <PERSON> Solomon </PER