<HEAD>Church of Nativity Roof Leak Causes Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A leaky roof on the church built over the grotto where <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> is believed to have been born has revived an ancient dispute among three Christian communities over control of the church. When the <ORGANIZATION> Greek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orthodox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> recently tried to repair the roof on the Church of the Nativity, Roman Catholics and the Armenians complained. Now the Israeli government has taken responsibility for repairs, an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> spokesman said Friday. `` The workers who were on the roof had to be ordered off,'' said <PERSON> Shmuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamburger </PERSON>, religious affairs officer for the military government of the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, where the church in <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION> is located. Hamburger said the argument dates to before 1852, when the then-Turkish government of Palestine stepped in to settle disputes among the three churches. An agreement known as `` the status quo'' was established to assign such responsibilities as cleaning the church, but roof repairs have always been disputed. `` The procedure in which the roof is repaired, from the time of the Turks, was done by the government,'' <PERSON> Hamburger </PERSON> said. Construction on the Church of the Nativity began in the 4th century. The Greek Orthodox Church gained title in 1672, but the Roman Catholics obtained partial ownership in 1852. The Armenians control a southern section of the church. The grotto where tradition says <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> was born is under the Greek Orthodox part of the church. The three churches jealously guard their rights as outlined in `` the status quo,'' and roof work done in 1983 also caused a dispute. The Rev. <PERSON> Claudio </PERSON> <PERSON> Baratto </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, said his church and the Armenians consider the roof common property and believe any repairs should be approved by all three churches. <PERSON> Baratto </PERSON> said the roof has been leaking for years and referred to it as part `` an ancient question'' over which the churches continue to argue. `` Some parts pretend to have rights that the other parts contest,'' he said. `` We hope in the future to reach a sensible solution,'' Baratto added. But for now, he said, the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> government will have to take responsibility for the repairs. Hamburger said they should be made after the rainy winter weather subsides. A spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Greek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orthodox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> could not be reached for comment. <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON>, secretary to the Greek Orthodox Patriarch, told the <ORGANIZATION> Jerusalem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> that the church was not trying to repair the roof but only to clean out rain gutters. He added, however, that the church has the right to make roof repairs if it wishes. `` If we wanted to do something, we would do it. I do n't think they had the right to complain,'' the newspaper quoted him as saying.
