<SECOND>AM-Hong Kong,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hong Kong Panel Bars Elected Official for 15 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A joint <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong-China </LOCATION> panel approved a measure Friday to bar the enclave from electing its own chief executive for at least 15 years after Chinese rule begins in 1997, a committee member said. However, the committee's political blueprint would also provide for increasing proportions of elected seats in the local legislature. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, a pro-democracy lawyer from <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> who sits on the committee, said the plan, which must be approved by <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, represents `` a big step backward as far as democracy was concerned.'' The proposal is included in a proposed constitution by which <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> will govern capitalist <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> after the British withdraw from the colony on <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s coast. The document is designed to enshrine the `` one country-two system'' plan promised by <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> to allow this territory of 5.7 million people to exercise a `` high degree of autonomy'' and remain capitalist for at least 50 years after the change in sovereignty. The 58-member committee with <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and Chinese representatives met in the nearby southern <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION> on Friday and approved most of the second draft to be submitted to the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. A third and final draft is expected to be approved by <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> next year. In an interview from <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said the group backed a plan under which the first three post-colonial chief executives, serving five-year terms, would be chosen by an electoral college. A governor appointed by <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> heads the colonial government. The chief executive will be post-colonial <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s top local official. Under the committee's proposal, a referendum could be held to determine whether the fourth chief executive will be popularly elected. However, the vote will take place only if half the members of the local legislature, the sitting chief executive and a committee of the Chinese congress approve, according to <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>. `` Effectively, we may never have a directly elected chief executive,'' said <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>. The committee also proposed that the first four post-1997 local legislatures, each lasting four years, be composed of directly elected members and interest group representatives, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said. Popularly elected members will constitute 27 percent of the first legislature, 38 percent of the second and 50 percent of the third and fourth. If a referendum is held, the public could decide whether all members are popularly elected, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said.
