<HEAD>Genetic `Print' Clears Accused Rapist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man who spent six months in jail facing rape charges was released Friday, cleared by a DNA print test that showed he could not have been the attacker. `` We're so happy,'' said <PERSON> Sammie </PERSON> <PERSON> Scheff </PERSON>'s mother, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>. `` It's been so bad. I knew he did n't do it. ... Now we can get on with our lives.'' <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowhey </PERSON> signed an order dismissing the charges against <PERSON> Scheff </PERSON>, 26, of <LOCATION> Greenburgh </LOCATION>, after the DNA tests cleared him. In an unusual move, the district attorney's office made the dismissal motion, backing a motion <PERSON> Scheff </PERSON>'s attorney had planned to make. `` It's about time,'' said <PERSON> Scheff </PERSON>, who left court and headed back to his job as a carpenter's assistant. The dismissal came a day after a hearing during which experts declared that the DNA tests proved `` 100 percent'' that <PERSON> Scheff </PERSON> could not have raped the 21-year-old woman outside a convenience store in <LOCATION> Greenburgh </LOCATION> on Feb. 8, 1988. <PERSON> Scheff </PERSON> was arrested Feb. 25 and imprisoned until Aug. 26, when his bail was reduced from $ 50,000 to $ 500, based largely on the test results. Prosecutor <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolen </PERSON> said his office would accept the DNA test results as scientific evidence. But his office asked for the hearing to determine if the tests were done properly. The victim had identified <PERSON> Scheff </PERSON> in a photo array and in a lineup, <PERSON> Bolen </PERSON> said. DNA print testing is a new, highly technical procedure based on the fact that each person's DNA, or genetic material, is unique, except in the case of identical twins. The DNA Print Identification Test offers comparisons of genetic codes by extracting the DNA from a crime scene specimen, such as semen, blood or tissue, and chemically dividing the DNA into fragments. The fragments form a pattern which serves as an identity profile. The pattern can be compared with the identity pattern from the suspect's blood specimen.
