<HEAD>Helms Says Soviets Violating Treaty At Missile Plant But US Is Satisfied</HEAD>
<HEAD>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.C. </LOCATION>, said Friday the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is preventing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inspectors from X-raying containers leaving a Soviet missile assembly plant and is therefore violating the treaty banning medium-range, nuclear-armed missiles. But the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said it expects full Soviet cooperation when the X-ray equipment is ready to be installed and is satisfied that existing procedures will enable the detection of any banned medium-range SS-20 missile attempting to leave the factory. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is satisfied with the implementation of the ... treaty to date,'' said department spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redmond </PERSON>. <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, in a letter to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, called inspection rights at Votkinsk the `` heart and keystone'' of the treaty's verification system and said that under the treaty's terms the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inspection team should have been able to X-ray all items leaving the factory by last Dec. 1, six months after the treaty went into effect. `` The package of procedures that the Soviets obligated themselves to allow have not been agreed, in part because the Soviets have made unacceptable demands for other procedures and provisions,'' <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> said. `` Because of this failure to agree to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> X-ray rights, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> X-ray equipment is still not installed at <LOCATION> Votkinsk </LOCATION>,'' he said. <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> what he intends to do to `` prevent the Soviets from continuing to exploit their potential to cheat at Votkinsk'' and added: `` Due to Soviet intransigence, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> has been totally unable to monitor effectively or verify whether the Soviets have continued to manufacture or deploy perhaps dozens of banned SS-20 missiles from the Votkinsk factory for the last eight months that the treaty has been in force.'' But at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Redmond </PERSON> said that any problem was a minor one. `` The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> agrees fully with the right of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to install that kind of equipment,'' <PERSON> Redmond </PERSON> said, adding that the Soviets will have the same X-raying privileges at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> facility at <ORGANIZATION> Magna </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>. `` We are now in the final stage of working out of the details of implementing this right,'' <PERSON> Redmon </PERSON> said. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is in the final stage of testing the appropriate equipment for this particular verification method.'' `` When we are fully ready to install our equipment we expect the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> will cooperate with us fully,'' he said. A 30-person <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> team continuously monitors the Votkinsk facility and has inspected every vehicle leaving it large enough to contain an SS-20, <PERSON> Redmon </PERSON> said. Additionally. he said the inspection team is `` opening randomly selected SS-25 canisters.'' `` This particular monitoring activity is but one element of a comprehensive set of verification procedures,'' <PERSON> Redmond </PERSON> said.
