<SECOND>AM-Drugs-Postal,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Postal Drug Tests May Indicate Problem Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 People who tested positive for drugs in pre-employment screening, but were hired anyway, had sharply higher absentee rates and were much more likely to be fired than other workers, the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> reported Friday. Once on the job, people who had positive drug tests had a 43 percent higher absentee rate and were 40 percent more likely to be fired than workers who tested clean of drugs, the agency said. `` We're doing actual work force performance factors. Attendance and involuntary turnover are the first ones -LRB- in which -RRB- we see a strong relationship at this point in the study,'' said Assistant Postmaster General <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Trosch </PERSON> in a telephone interview. `` Frankly, I anticipate some of the relationships we see getting stronger and I will not be surprised if we see other relationships'' such as accident rates, he said. `` Even these first interim results provide significant support for a business decision to say no to applicants who test positive for drugs,'' added <PERSON> Trosch </PERSON>, who handles employee relations. The drug tests were not used in deciding whether to hire the employees involved, although the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> is planning to institute pre-employment drug screening for all new workers over the next 30 days, <PERSON> Trosch </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, is considering whether such testing should be subject to bargaining between the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and its unions. The test results reported Friday came from a program involving 4,375 workers hired at 21 sites around the country over nine months. The report covered the first six months of work for those people. It is planned to continue for a full two years. In the test, designed by the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> with <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abuse </ORGANIZATION> consultation, job applicants were screened for drugs before being hired. However, local managers were not informed of the results of the tests. They made hiring decisions based on written exams and interviews, as with any postal worker, officials said. In the study, 5,465 applicants were screened for drugs. Of them, 4,375 were eventually hired by the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, and 4,220 were evaluated in this study because they had completed their six-month probationary period. A subsequent analysis found that 515 applicants had tested positive, of which 354 had been hired by the agency. Marijuana was the most common drug found, being detected in 232 cases. Of those hired, 88 had tested positive for cocaine and 34 for other drugs, according to the report. Of all those hired, 361 have since been fired by the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> for one reason or another, the report said. That group included 42 people who had tested positive for drugs and 319 who had tested negative. The study found those using drugs made up 8.4 percent of the evaluated group of people hired. The firing rate for drug users was 40 percent higher than for non-users. In addition, the agency totaled up the sick leave, leave without pay and time spent absent without leave for both groups. While it did not report detailed numbers in this category, the agency said that those who had tested positive for drugs were absent from work at a rate 43 percent greater than those who tested negative. `` Our study is the first in which we are ... comparing performance of individuals who test positive and who test negative in an actual work setting,'' <PERSON> Trosch </PERSON> said. In reporting the preliminary figures, the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> added that turnover and absenteeism are only two of many areas that are potentially affected by whether workers use drugs. `` Other productivity savings may result from reductions in accidents, injuries, benefit claims, etc.,'' the report said. Statistics on those topics are expected to be included as the test continues. The 21 postal centers involved in the test are <LOCATION> Trenton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Haven </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>; two hiring centers in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and two hiring centers in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
