<FIRST>r i AM-Canada-Tritium     01-13 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Tritium,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canada Unlikely to Resolve Any U.S. Tritium Shortage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tritium, a gas that strengthens nuclear bombs, is a byproduct of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s nuclear power plants, but the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should n't look to the north for a way to ease a shortage caused by problems in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> weapons plants. `` It would not be amenable,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Spence </PERSON>. `` In peacetime certainly it would not be amenable. Certainly we would not countenance sales directly to the weapons system.'' Anti-nuclear activists allege that any exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would be virtually impossible to track in their civilian or military uses. `` Even if our tritium is n't used directly in military weapons systems, which we suspect it will be, it will free up their scarce supplies,'' <PERSON> Irene </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> of the Nuclear Awareness Project said in a telephone interview. The <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plant </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Aiken </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, the only <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> source of the radioactive isotope of hydrogen, is closed because of safety problems. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> has recommended building two new production reactors, at a cost of $ 8.6 billion. Meanwhile, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> needs to replenish the tritium, which decays at a rate of 5.5 percent a year, in its warheads. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> nuclear industry is based on light-water reactors, which use water as a coolant and other materials as moderators _ slowing the neutrons enough so they cause fission. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s 18 reactors use heavy water _ in which hydrogen is replaced by the isotope deuterium _ as coolant and moderator. One byproduct of the reaction is tritium, which also has some commercial and industrial applications, including in emergency lighting devices. `` Right now the plan is to remove the tritium and then store it on site,'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. `` We still have n't made that decision to sell any of it, let alone export any of it to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>'' The question of exports came up in the debate over the plant 47 miles east of <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>, `` mainly from the critics who oppose this,'' he said `` It's very much an issue for us. It has been for a couple of years,'' said <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>, whose group is pressuring the <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION> provincial government to refuse permission for any tritium exports. The federal government also would have to license exports of radioactive materials, and <PERSON> Spence </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> has one of the world's most stringest systems of safeguards against nuclear exports for any military purposes It requires countries with recognized nuclear capacities _ the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> _ to agree that no Canadian materials will be used for weapons. In general, other countries must have `` full-scope safeguards'' to obtain Canadian materials, and must allow international inspection of all nuclear facilities. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> was cut off in 1974. It also is recognized that exports for peaceful uses free a supply for weapons systems, although that has not come up in any debate, <PERSON> Spence </PERSON> said. `` I know the Americans know our safeguard concerns and in many ways share them.'' <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has not approached the <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> government for tritium, he said. `` It really has n't come up.''
