<HEAD>Four Killed, 200 Wounded In Sikh-Hindu Clash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JAMMU, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hindus and Sikhs fought with guns and swords Friday during a religious procession honoring two Sikhs executed for the assassination of Prime Minister <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandi </PERSON>, authorities and witnesses said. Civil administrator N.R. <PERSON> Gupta </PERSON> said at least four people, including a Sikh trapped in a burning truck, were killed. About 200 people were injured, and more than 200 shops were looted and set ablaze, he said. The government of <LOCATION> Jammu-Kashmir </LOCATION> state imposed a curfew on the northern city and ordered police to shoot violators. Police opened fire several times and used tear gas to try to stop the fighting, but it continued until 1,000 army troops arrived more than five hours later, <PERSON> Gupta </PERSON> said. Witnesses said the fighting started shortly after about 2,000 Sikhs left a temple on a procession in honor of <PERSON> Kehar </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> and <PERSON> Satwant </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, who were hanged last week and now are revered as martyrs of the Sikh faith. Many carried pictures as the eight-mile procession moved through a Hindu neighborhood, and a group of militant Hindus asked the Sikhs to remove the pictures, the witnesses said. One Sikh pulled a dagger and lunged at the Hindus, who retaliated, they said. <LOCATION> Jammu </LOCATION>, 40 miles north of Sikh-dominated <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state, has a population of about 500,000. Of these, about 80,000 are <PERSON> Sikhs </PERSON>, about 300,000 are Hindus and the rest are Moslems. <PERSON> Kehar </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> and <PERSON> Satwant </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> were executed for the assassination of Mrs. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>, who was killed Oct. 31, 1984, in apparent retaliation for an army raid she had ordered on the Sikhs' holy Golden Temple. Sikh militants were using the temple as a base for their fight for an independent homeland in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state. The assassination caused anti-Sikh riots in many northern cities, including <LOCATION> Jammu </LOCATION>. More than 2,700 people died, most of them Sikhs. Sikhs comprise 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 800 million people but are a majority in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. Sikh militants claim discrimination by <PERSON> Hindus </PERSON>, who comprise 80 percent of the country's population.
