<HEAD>Official Says Prosecution Of Firm Will Require ``Complete Evidence''
^With AM-Germany-Libya Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The West German finance minister said Friday his government had `` some new information'' to link firms in his country with the construction of a plant in <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> says was designed to develop chemical weapons. But the West German official said criminal prosecution would proceed only if there was `` complete evidence.'' <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoltenberg </PERSON> pledged after a one-hour meeting with Deputy Secretary of State <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitehead </PERSON> that `` whatever it takes to get information, it will be followed.'' Meanwhile, West German and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> experts held a second day of meetings on the intelligence the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has used to support its claim that <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> was trying to develop chemical weapons at the plant, some 60 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION>. `` We are trying to provide as much information as possible,'' <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said. He said the talks at an undisclosed location would be `` useful and productive,'' but provided no other details. Separate British and Dutch investigations also point to an attempt by Col. <PERSON> Moammar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON>'s country to develop chemical weapons. Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said last week the Libyans had not reached the point of production. <PERSON> Stoltenberg </PERSON>, in a curbside news conference outside the department, renewed allegations that West German firms had been targeted for criticism by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> media. `` What we did not like in some <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> press comments,'' he said, `` was to single out <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> because it is obvious that it could have been a problem of quite a few other countries.'' The finance minister said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> should join in promoting international cooperation to prevent technology transfers to countries which could produce chemical weapons to endanger world security. Officials of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> German </LOCATION> government last week registered skepticism that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had evidence to link West German firms to the plant, which <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON> said was producing pharmaceuticals. However, Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> said Thursday in <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> that authorities had seized new documents that may show firms helped the North African country build a chemical plant. On Friday, <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Frey </PERSON>, a spokesman for the prosecutor's office in <LOCATION> Karlsrube </LOCATION>, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> there would be an investigation into the Imhausen-Chemie company. <PERSON> Frey </PERSON> said the possible charge being investigated was `` a violation of the export control law.'' He did not elaborate. Imhausen-Chemie has denied any connection to the Libyan plant. <PERSON> Stoltenberg </PERSON> said the evidence came from West German sources. `` There was no proof a week ago,'' he said, `` and now there is some new information in the last days ... which could lead to criminal prosecution.'' But he said `` it's not a final decision ... We must have complete evidence -LRB- to prosecute -RRB-. Whatever it takes to get information, it will be followed.'' Referring to the dispute with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the West German official said `` we have really made progress in understanding.''
