<HEAD>Two Journalists Lied On Applications, Got Jobs At Heathrow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two British journalists said Friday they got jobs as airplane cleaners at <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> using fake applications and were able to wander on and off jets where they could easily have planted bombs. One of them, a <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weekend </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> researcher, said he left a package on a <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> flight without being challenged. The other, <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> reporter <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> <PERSON> Dudman </PERSON>, said he was hired by <ORGANIZATION> Skyliner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> after a 10-minute interview and found `` alarming holes'' in <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> security three weeks after a bomb was planted on Pan Am Flight 103. The two journalists were not working together when they got their airport jobs. The British Airports Authority, which operates <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION>, refused comment. <PERSON> Dudman </PERSON> said he decided to apply at the airport after a bomb blew up Flight 103 on Dec. 21, killing all 259 people on board and 11 people on the ground in the Scottish town of <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>. The New York-bound flight originated in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> and switched to a bigger plane at <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dudman </PERSON> said he was hired by <ORGANIZATION> Skyliner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, a private cleaning contractor, after an interview Jan. 4. He said his application, which contained many lies, was never checked. <PERSON> Dudman </PERSON> said he received a pass that allowed him access to all areas of the airport, and he started work Jan. 9. `` As a part-time aircraft cleaner, it enabled me to board 12 jetliners on any one of which I could have planted a bomb under a seat or in a locker,'' he said. `` I gained unchallenged access to luggage containers and the cabin and flight decks of trans-Atlantic airlines where at times I was alone and unsupervised,'' he said. <PERSON> Dudman </PERSON> said he carried bulky packages and a camera past security posts and was never stopped or questioned, even when he took photographs on the airfield. Several photographs appeared in the paper, including one that showed the reporter posing near some Pan Am luggage. `` Each member of the cleaming staff I spoke to about security said they had never seen any and expressed amazement there had been no clampdown after <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Dudman </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weekend </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> said researcher <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> was hired by <PERSON> Fernley </PERSON> <PERSON> Aeroclean </PERSON>, using a fake name. It said he planted a parcel on <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> Flight 402. <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> said he was n't searched when boarding planes or supervised while working and could have planted the parcel anywhere, except possibly <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> which ran a metal detector over the cabin after the cleaners had finished. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, a reporter for <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weekend </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION>, said after he received a call from <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, he bought a ticket on Flight 402, retrieved the package from under a window seat during the flight and took it into the cockpit without challenge. `` It could have contained a bomb, a gun or a knife,'' he said. `` I could easily have blown up or hijacked the plane.'' <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weekend </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> said the incident was filmed and would be shown Sunday, subject to approval by the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>. After <PERSON> Dudman </PERSON>'s disclosure, <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION>'s managing director, <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Proctor </PERSON>, announced that <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> had withdrawn security passes for staff at Skyliner. Transport Secretary <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Channon </PERSON> ordered the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airports </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> to tighten security to ensure no one had unsupervised access to aircraft or checked baggage in restricted areas unless they had held an airport pass for at least six months. Skyliner called the government's action `` a very harsh decision because procedures for security are the same with us as they are for all the other companies at <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION>.''
