<HEAD>Landlord Who Refused to Rent to Unwed Couple Challenges State Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARSHALL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man being sued by the state for refusing to rent to an unmarried couple is challenging the state Human Rights Act, which he says violates his religious beliefs forbidding sex before marriage. `` The Bible clearly states this is wrong,'' Layle French, 32, said Thursday from his farm outside <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, in southwestern <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. `` I live with the Bible as my guide.'' French said the Human Rights Act, which protects Minnesotans from various forms of discrimination, violates his First Amendment right to freedom of religion and is unconstitutional. The dispute began last February when <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Parsons </PERSON> of <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> sought to rent a house owned by French. <PERSON> Parsons </PERSON> and French entered into an agreement in which <PERSON> Parsons </PERSON> told French she intended to live with her fiance and that his two children would stay with thempart of every month, according to a <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> complaint. Two days later, French told <PERSON> Parsons </PERSON> he had changed his mind and would not rent to her. French said he told her, `` Why do n't you get married and I'll let you rent it.'' He and his attorney, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, filed a written response Friday with the state attorney general's office to the lawsuit filed Dec. 7 by the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>. An administrative law judge is scheduled to hear the case April 11. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said the law's lack of a provision for a jury trial makes it unconstitutional. Human Rights Commissioner <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> said juries do not hear human rights cases because juries are supposed to reflect the society's majority, and human rights laws are designed to protect the minority. He said French was trying to control the lives of his tenants. `` Landlords often have exaggerated ideas of what their rights are,'' <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> said. `` They're trying to invent a constitutional right to say, ` I have the right to tell you what to think.''' French said he believes by living together the couple would violate a little-known state statute that outlaws sexual intercourse between unmarried adults. `` We contend it's a very schizophrenic state that on the one hand outlaws fornication and on the other compels cohabitation,'' said <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>. `` It's against his religious convictions to rent on that basis.'' He conceded that the misdemeanor sex statute was rarely enforced although still on the books. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> said French had no evidence <PERSON> Parsons </PERSON> and her fiance would violate the law forbidding sex before marriage. Phone calls to <PERSON> Parsons </PERSON>' home for comment Friday went unanswered.
