<HEAD>Official Says Lost Missile Part Would Be Valuable To Soviets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A flight data recorder missing from a 1987 long-range nuclear missile test would provide valuable information to any <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> adversary that might have recovered the device, an <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official said Friday. Although the recorder contained no classified information, `` it is valuable,'' said <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Sankey </PERSON>, a department spokeswoman. She declined to describe the specific value of the recorder to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> or any other country. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> acknowledged earlier this week it was investigating the loss of the recorder and said there was a possibility it may have been found by the Soviets. Defense officials also said the recording device, which would contain such information as the acceleration and velocity of the missile during flight, was not classified. But a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> source indicated the data would be valuable to a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> adversary since the missile was being tested under realistic conditions. `` Would n't you like to get your hands on that?'' asked the source. <PERSON> Sankey </PERSON> said a search for the device was continuing jointly by the departments of defense and energy but there was no clear evidence it had fallen into Soviet hands. The Energy Department is responsible for building and testing the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s nuclear warheads. During test flights the missiles carry a dummy warhead and not an actual nuclear weapon, although the rest of the missile contents are real. Ms. <PERSON> Sankey </PERSON> said only the flight date recorder and `` some minor debris'' were lost during the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> recovery of the Minuteman 2 missile that was launched July 7, 1987 from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> toward <ORGANIZATION> Kwajalein </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atoll </ORGANIZATION> in the western <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>. She said this was the first time that a missile's flight data recorder had been lost in a test flight. `` It does n't pose a loss of any technology for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, but obviously there are a lot of things unclassified that we do n't want non-allied countries to have,'' Ms. <PERSON> Sankey </PERSON> said
