<HEAD>Stoltenberg Says US, Allies to Meet on Third World Debt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> will meet with cabinet members from six major allies to prepare for a major gathering on Third World debt, West German Finance Minister <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoltenberg </PERSON> said Friday. The `` Group of Seven'' includes <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. Their ministers of finance and the heads of their central banks meet at irregular intervals to try and bring their economic policies closer together and coordinate policy on the dollar and other currencies. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Levine </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>, said no decision has been made on the meeting. Support for it has now also been voiced by <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>, the British chancellor of the exchequer, who saw <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> earlier this week. The presidents of seven major Latin American debtor countries will be meeting in <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> Feb. 2 at the inauguration of <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> as president of <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> and the recently inaugurated President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> have taken the lead in urging relief from the debt burden that has resulted in net payments of $ 20 to $ 30 billion a year from poor countries to richer ones. <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, one of the most regular with its payments, at length joined many of the other debtor governments and suspended payments of principal on most of its $ 30.3 billion debt on Dec. 31. There have been reports that <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> is considering a stop on interest as well. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, who will be inaugurated next week as vice-president, will represent the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> at the inauguration. Latin American countries owe more than $ 440 billion of the $ 1.3 trillion of Third World debt. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> are the biggest Third World debtors, with much of the money owed to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks. In April, representatives of 151 countries, including many cabinet members, will be in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for a semi-annual meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>. The debt and how to reduce it will be major topics there. The seven governments try to coordinate their buying and selling of currencies to keep the prices as stable as possible. <PERSON> Stoltenberg </PERSON> said that would continue while plans are worked out by the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration to reduce the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> budget deficit, a goal strongly urged by the allies.
</TEXT>
