<FIRST>r a AM-BoneSuit     01-13 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bone Suit,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Malpractice Settlements Reach $5.3 Million In Bone Peg Cases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four medical malpractice suits against a doctor who replaced patients' spinal discs with bone taken from cadavers have been settled for $ 5.3 million, said lawyers for the plaintiffs. <PERSON> Aaron </PERSON> <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON>, an orthopedic surgeon, used a garden hose to wash the bone pegs cut from pelvic bones of cadavers at the <LOCATION> Pinellas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> morgue, after getting permission from next of kin, lawyers said. He then stored the bone pegs in his kitchen freezer, they said. Three other malpractice suits against <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON> are pending. The latest settlement of $ 975,000 was reached Tuesday, 90 minutes into the testimony from the first witness during the trial of a suit brought by <PERSON> Dolores </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, 47, of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Petersburg </LOCATION>. Her lawyers said she suffered crippling pain and a severe loss of mobility because of the procedure. `` Nobody that I know uses this procedure,'' testified Dr. <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Greene </PERSON>, an orthopedic surgeon from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION>'s medical school. <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON>'s insurer, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> Patients Compensation Fund, agreed to settle while <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> was testifying. In earlier court proceedings, <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON> denied he committed malpractice, but he declined to comment after the settlement. The procedure is not experimental but is considered difficult and requires extensive training, said <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> lawyer <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, who represented Mrs. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON> performed the operation 107 times on 58 people, and his own records showed a success rate of 24 percent, said another lawyer for Mrs. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Bianchi </PERSON>. <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON> told Mrs. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, who injured her back in a 1981 fall, that replacing a disc with a bone peg had a 90 percent chance of alleviating her pain, according to court papers. Mrs. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>'s pain, however, worsened after the operation at <LOCATION> Humana-Sun </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Community </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Petersburg </LOCATION>, and she sustained nerve injury, the suit said. She underwent two more operations, one using more bone pegs from a cadaver and the other using bone chisled from Mrs. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>'s hip. In the end, she had 14 different bone pegs hammered in and nine chisled out, the suit said. The hospital also was named in the suit but was dropped from the case Monday after agreeing to a small settlement, that was not disclosed. Prior settlements reached in the last six months have ranged from $ 247,500 to $ 2,062,000. Three more cases are set for trial later this year. The <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Professional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulation </ORGANIZATION> has no public record of any investigation or discipline involving <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON>, a spokesman said.
</TEXT>
