<FIRST>r w AM-TritiumAlternative     01-13 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tritium Alternative,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sources Say DOE Put Accelerator Report `On Ice''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Department of Energy held back for several months a report that concluded there was a cheaper, quicker and safer way to produce tritium for nuclear weapons than building a new production reactor, sources familiar with the report said Friday. A copy of a draft summary of the report obtained by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> said a linear accelerator could produce enough tritium to meet all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> weapons needs. The report, which still has not been released, was prepared by scientists at the department's <ORGANIZATION> Brookhaven </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alamos </LOCATION> national laboratories and the <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse-Hanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a department contractor based at the <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION> nuclear reservation in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state. The draft summary was dated August 1988, a month after the department had recommended construction of two new production reactors and at a time when there was deepening concern about the safety and reliability of the entire weapons complex, particularly the tritium-producing reactors at <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. The sources, who asked not to be identified, said Friday that department officials were worried that release of the report would provide further ammunition for critics of the department's decision to build new reactors. They also said officials feared the report could cause problems at a time when the department was struggling to get its defense production programs back on track. The sources said the department wanted the report held until after the election and the new administration took office. `` I think the words were ` put it on ice,''' said one source at the <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION> reservation familiar with the report. `` They wanted to hide it under a rug.'' Another source, who worked on the report, said that as word of the study started to seep out to the scientific community, there were subtle suggestions to scientists at <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alamos </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION> that they not discuss it. The source also said the report had yet to receive a fair hearing from the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and that those who have seen it at the department have been skeptical about its conclusions. <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Sankey </PERSON>, a department spokeswoman, denied that the department had been holding the report. `` We've not directed any such effort to put such a report on hold,'' she said. `` To my knowledge the department has not formally reviewed and therefore is not prepared to discuss this particular proposal. `` I would point out that pursuance of other technologies to meet long-term national security requirements is consistent with the objectives of our national laboratories and contractors.'' Ms. <PERSON> Sankey </PERSON> had said earlier that the department's <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> looked briefly at the idea of using an accelerator to produce tritium, but concluded that the technology was not `` mature enough to provide new production capacity.'' An accelerator is essentially a long tunnel in which subatomic particles are whipped at high speed until they crash into a target, in this case lithium clad in aluminum. The resulting collision produces tritium, a radioactive gas used in nuclear warheads. The draft report said that an accelerator would produce far less radioactive waste, would not operate at the high pressures and extreme temperatures and `` should be more acceptable to the public'' than a nuclear reactor.
</TEXT>
