<HEAD>Red Army Leaves Kabul in the Cold</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS four grafs after 5th, `They (</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Alongside the icy runway at <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>'s airport, about 500 Soviet soldiers laden with equipment lined up Friday in front of giant transport planes waiting to take them back to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> Downtown, Afghans huddled in blankets against the biting cold, forming long lines for bread or gasoline. Bread, the staple diet of the poor, has become a precious and increasingly expensive commodity. Afghan guerrillas, assisted by a bitter winter, appear to be making an increasingly effective attempt to blockade the city of 3 million, and some diplomats say the Soviet strategy is to get out as quickly as possible, with as little publicity as possible. Indeed, Friday's troop departure was the latest in what Western diplomats say is a rapidly accelerating pullout that belies hints from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> it may not meet next month's withdrawal deadline. `` They -LRB- the Soviet troops -RRB- are leaving and they want to cover up the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> end of it,'' said one Western diplomat. `` It could be that with the acute shortages, they do n't want to show the unpleasant reality of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>.'' But the Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said Friday: `` An extremely difficult situation developed in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> in providing the population with foodstuffs. Long breadlines appeared in the city.'' It reported that the government imposed an anti-hoarding decree under which `` people who deliberately hide surplus foodstuffs and do not hand them over in time, are brought to court.'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said convoys of food, fuel and other necessities were being rushed into <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, but `` groups of extremists attack convoys virtually every day and are a constant threat to <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>'s supplies.'' Afghan government forces killed or wounded 100 insurgents in battles in <LOCATION> Nangarhar </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kandahar </LOCATION> provinces, and near <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> seized 54 missiles intended for use against the capital city, the news agency said. Another 170 resistance fighters were killed or wounded in fighting among rival factions, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. Under a U.N.-mandated agreement, the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, which entered <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in December 1979, is to be out of the country by Feb. 15. Soldiers began leaving May 15, and about half the estimated 100,000 were gone by Aug. 15. But the Moslem guerrillas fighting the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> and Afghan troops this week broke off negotiations with <PERSON> Yuli </PERSON> <PERSON> Vorontsov </PERSON>, the Soviet deputy foreign minister and the ambassador to <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Vorontsov </PERSON> hinted that if the insurgency continued, the Soviet troops might delay their departure. Western diplomats say the current rate of withdrawal indicates the bulk of the Soviet troops are likely to be gone ahead of schedule. Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> traveled to <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> on Friday. The nature of his visit was not disclosed by <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>. Friday's group of troops was lined up beside two blue and white Ilyushin-76 transport planes. More than a dozen smaller Antonov aircraft were nearby. Diplomats estimate that seven to eight Il-76 aircraft arrive and leave daily. This week, the Soviets shut down their 700-bed military hospital in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, pulled out all the medical staff and handed the facility over to the Afghan administration. Soviet civilian advisers as well as government ministers are also going. There are no firm numbers on how many of the estimated 2,500 advisers remain. Diplomats say that in the past week, the number of advisers at the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> has been cut from 16 to two and at the <ORGANIZATION> Afghan-Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> from 20 to five. The price of nan, the flat bread that along with sugar and tea is all most Afghans can reguarly afford, has more than doubled to about 15 Afghanis. At the commonly used black market rate, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar is worth 200 Afghanis. Sugar ran out at most stores about a month ago. On Sunday, a regular working day in this Moslem country, the bread shortage was so acute that 80 percent of bread stores were closed. Witnesses said a group of Afghan soldiers broke into and robbed one store that still had supplies. Large parts of the city are without power for up to six hours daily. In what appears to be part of an effort to conserve power, the university closed in November, a month early, and wo n't reopen until March, a month late. Thos who can afford it are exacerbating the shortages by stocking up. People join cars at gas stations, filling up two-gallon cans to lug home. One Western diplomat estimated that up to 7,000 of the remaining 50,000 Soviet soldiers may have left since the new year. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Jan. 11 that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> had renewed its withdrawal from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Army Gen. <PERSON> Vitaly </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shabanov </PERSON>, a deputy Soviet defense minister, told a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> news conference Friday: `` It is our intention to abide by the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> agreements. This is our duty and indeed this is the firm opinion and strong intention of our leaders. So there can be no doubts in this regard.''
