<HEAD>Treasury Considering Merger of Bank and S&amp;L Agencies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is working on a savings and loan reform plan that would transfer control of the insurance fund for <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L deposits from its current regulatory parent to the agency that insures commercial banks, a government official said Friday. However, the department has n't decided for certain on the recommendation to President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, which would give the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> jurisdiction over the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. It would be an administrative merger, not a merger of the money in the funds, which are each separately financed through premiums paid by the industry they insure, the official said. Commercial bankers are lobbying hard to make sure money from their fund does n't go to solve a competing industry's problems. The <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> is solvent, with more than $ 15 billion in reserves. The <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION>, although it still has several billion dollars in cash to work with, has been technically insolvent since 1986. An administrative merger of the funds would promote similar regulatory standards for both banks and <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls. Bankers believe that regulation of S & amp; Ls is now more lax. The <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> already regulates institutions, called savings banks, which are similar to savings and loan associations. Even so, many in the S & amp; L industry believe merging the funds would eventually mean the end of a separate system of providing home mortgage loans. Currently, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> runs the <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION>, which as the deposit insuror has prime responsibility for making sure <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls engage in safe lending practices. However, the bank board is also charged with promoting home ownership by establishing S & amp; Ls, a role critics say can inherently conflict with the FSLICs. The Wall Street Journal, in Friday's editions, cited sources who said the department is close to deciding in favor of the FSLIC-FDIC merger, but is still considering whether to recommend abolishing the bank board altogether. S & amp; L regulators reacted strongly against both proposals, which could be forwarded to President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as soon as he takes office on Jan. 20. `` I think it's a crummy idea,'' said bank board member <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>. `` It does not get us any kind of pot of gold that's going to solve the problem. I do n't think you get any better regulation. ... What it does do is create administrative disruption and disarray at exactly the wrong time.'' <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Seidman </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION>, has in several speeches expressed his agency's preference `` for going it alone,'' however, he has said he would, if asked, tackle the job of regulating S & amp; Ls in addition to banks. In a study released earlier this month, the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> recommended that <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION> be made independent of the bank board, but remain separate from the <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION>. Treasury is also examining ways to find a source of money to devote to faster rescues and closings of insolvent S & amp; Ls. Proposals range from a mechanism to borrow the money `` off-budget'' so that it does not inflate the budget deficit to spending the money outright, but declaring it exempt from Gramm-Rudman deficit limits. A senior member of both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and the tax-writing <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Gradison </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ohio </LOCATION>, suggested Friday a rationale for exempting <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L rescue spending from Gramm-Rudman. <PERSON> Gradison </PERSON> released a <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> report that argued that the economic impact of <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L failures has already been felt because the losses already exist as a liability of the government, regardless of when the payoff actually occurs. `` The bailout should be reflected in the budget, but because the economic impact has already been absorbed, the resulting outlays should be exempt from the Gramm-Rudman targets,'' he said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s outgoing budget director, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, told reporters Friday he favored putting the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L rescue `` on-budget,'' rather than hiding the spending through some budgetary device. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, meanwhile, moved this week to establish an independent source of expertise on S & amp; Ls in the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> by naming <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Porter </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> business professor, as chief domestic policy adviser, and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> attorney, as an assistant for issues analysis.
