camera crews. The Hartz @ Meek press release was distributed before the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> issued its formal release announcing the government was seeking a $ 3.1 million contempt-of-court judgment against the <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> government for failing to upgrade the sewage plant. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said he was unaware of the private company's news release. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said he had been unable to get clearance from the attorney general's staff for <PERSON> Marzulla </PERSON> to hold a press conference. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said <PERSON> Marzulla </PERSON> had sought clearance from Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>'s office to hold a press conference. The spokesman said he was prepared to advise <PERSON> Marzulla </PERSON> not to hold a press conference when he was told the assistant attorney general had withdrawn his request for clearance. <PERSON> Marzulla </PERSON> said he asked <PERSON> Hartz </PERSON> @ Meek to issue the release to give local news organizations notice that the department's action was being taken. More publicity is needed, <PERSON> Marzulla </PERSON> said because the department's anti-pollution efforts have been `` eclipsed by the wrong notion that there has not been enough enforcement. He denied seeking to promote his new career as an environmental lawyer by using the public relations firm to summon local reporters to the briefing. `` It does not strike me as inappropriate,'' <PERSON> Marzulla </PERSON> said.
