<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> told Soviet and American high school exchange students Friday that as they get to know one another, they will discover `` that most of the problems in this world between countries do not exist between people.'' Turning to the Soviet youngsters, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said, `` What with our political parties and our open elections, all of the independent media, free labor unions, private businesses and private organizations of every type and size, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> has more different, independent participants in our system than we have flavors of ice cream.'' `` And believe me we have a lot of flavors of ice cream,'' he added. To the Americans, who will spend time in Soviet homes, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said, `` I think you will find that as people we share so much _ above all, we share our common humanity and our dreams of peace and freedom and a decent life for ourselves and our children.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> proposed the high school exchange program to Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> when they met in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> last year and told the students he is happy to see it under way before he leaves office. Later Friday, Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> ambassador <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubinin </PERSON> spoke to a welcoming assembly at a high school in suburban <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, where 15 Soviet students will be visiting for the next several weeks. `` You're part of something quite significant,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. He told the Soviet students `` you have a job to do ... to learn as much as you can'' about the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dubinin </PERSON> said `` this exchange is one of the spectacular results'' from the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit,