<HEAD>Faye Dunaway Can Only Be Herself</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 She won an Academy Award for playing the ruthless television executive in `` Network,'' and gave unforgettable performances as <PERSON> Bonnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> in `` <PERSON> Bonnie </PERSON> and Clyde'' and <PERSON> Evelyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulwray </PERSON> in `` <LOCATION> Chinatown </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Faye </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunaway </PERSON>'s exhaustive preparation and demand for perfection have won her admiration but have also caused tension on the set. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicholson </PERSON>, her co-star in `` <LOCATION> Chinatown </LOCATION>,'' nicknamed her `` The Dreaded Dunaway.'' But for her latest movie, `` Burning Secret,'' <PERSON> Dunaway </PERSON> drops the tempo. She plays <PERSON> Sonya </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuchman </PERSON>, the wife of an American diplomat stationed in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> in 1919. The film has a quiet, somber feel and <PERSON> Dunaway </PERSON> plays her part with the same sense of understatement. `` You just have to keep it balanced inside,'' the actress said. `` It's a part of acting. Your business is the inner character and the rest will take care of itself. `` This particular character was gently restrained. She was very much in the period of 1919, very much as it should be. She was n't like <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> in ` Network.' `` Burning Secret'' also stars <PERSON> Klaus </PERSON> <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Brandauer </PERSON> -LRB- `` Mephisto'' and `` Out of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'' -RRB- as the enigmatic baron who romances <PERSON> Sonya </PERSON>, and features 12-year-old <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Eberts </PERSON> in his film debut as <PERSON> Sonya </PERSON>'s sensitive son `` What <PERSON> Klaus </PERSON> does is what the best actors do,'' <PERSON> Dunaway </PERSON> said. `` He's a link. He always goes against the grain. He's also a very great gentleman.'' <PERSON> Dunaway </PERSON>, who has played opposite such seasoned thespians as <PERSON> War