<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:ReaganIcons ADV17   01-13 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Reagan Icons, ADV 17,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs, Jan 17 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gallery Showcases Images of Reagan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEWISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is a mythical centaur. He's also Rocky, a human television set and a warrior in what is billed as the first art exhibit to feature a sitting president These images of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> by nearly 40 artists, including <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grooms </ORGANIZATION>, appear in an exhibit titled `` <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>: American Icon'' at <ORGANIZATION> Bucknell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s Center Gallery. The show, featuring works done in the past eight years, opened Jan. 14 and will run through March 23. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will yield the presidency to <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Jan. 20. `` It's unprecedented that a president has had contemporary artists do this many images of him,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzger </PERSON>, the gallery's director, who added that the exhibit was the first of its kind for a president still in office. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> interpretations range from flattering to critical, but <PERSON> Metzger </PERSON> was quick to point out the exhibit was put together based on the quality of the art, not politics. `` You do n't go out of your way to offend someone with an art exhibit, but on the other hand, art is not docile. We do want to arouse people; we want to make them think,'' he said. The show includes: _ Two <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> screenprints of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Heusen </PERSON> shirt advertisements published during the president's acting days. _ A mock wooden toy by Red Grooms showing <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> standing on a missile connected to four wagon wheels titled `` Nuclear Nuts.'' _ A heroic depiction of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> as a centaur _ half horse, half man _ by the Moscow-born artists <PERSON> Komar </PERSON> and <PERSON> Melamid </PERSON>. _ A ceramic image by <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Arneson </PERSON> of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> as a television set, the president's smiling face coming out of the screen, a wire hand as the antenna and a warning on the back: `` Do not expose this appliance to thought or reason.'' _ A painting by Israeli-born artist <PERSON> Ori </PERSON> <PERSON> Hofmekler </PERSON> titled `` Ronnie II'' showing <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> as the <PERSON> Sylvester </PERSON> <PERSON> Stallone </PERSON> movie character Rocky Balboa, sporting boxing gloves and shorts and wearing a championship belt with the presidential seal on it. _ A lifelike portrait of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> by <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> McFadden </PERSON>, with the president's face covered by tiny, nearly invisible logos of all of the Fortune 500 companies. The show contains two paintings of <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and one of the president and first lady together. It also has books, articles, posters, photographs, buttons, T-shirts and postcards about the Reagans culled from <PERSON> Metzger </PERSON>'s personal collection of 50,000 books and 50 filing cabinets filled with memorabilia about celebrities ranging from <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> to the artist <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> <PERSON> Pollock </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzger </PERSON> said he conceived the idea for the show several years ago but did not think enough work with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> as the subject would exist until at least 1991. To find the work, <PERSON> Metzger </PERSON> quizzed museum directors, talked to artists and went to galleries in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. `` It was just detective work tracking down the material,'' he said. `` When I began the search I did n't know there was enough for a show. I was sort of groping. Who would have guessed?'' <PERSON> Metzger </PERSON>, who has a doctorate in art history from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> signed by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> when he was <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s governor, said the show is historically significant because it is done by artists while <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was still in office. `` This will be a show that will be a watershed,'' he said. `` There's probably no other show at any other museum devoted to one person. There just is n't the material.'' Even though almost all of the images of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> depict him in his role as president, it was <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s former life as an actor which attracted the artists, <PERSON> Metzger </PERSON> said. `` I do think it's this duality of his life. ... It's captured the imagination of a lot of contemporary artists,'' he said.
</TEXT>
