<TEXT>
 They do, engaging in fierce bidding wars, offering free land and water, road and sewer improvements, employee training funds and tax abatements. Chrysler-Mitsubishi received $ 88.7 million in state incentives alone, including 630 acres of farm land. `` Nobody ever offered us a site in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> ... Detroit ... -LRB- or -RRB- <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> said. Experts also say Japanese automakers prefer areas where unions are n't strong. `` They're afraid wages will be high,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` They're afraid unions will create demands that will make the company unproductive.'' <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> is atypical _ it is 25 miles from <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> and, spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Gill </PERSON> said, the only wholly owned subsidiary of a Japanese automaker with <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> affiliation. `` If you're going to locate in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Gill </PERSON> said, `` you best be prepared to deal with the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>.'' <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION>, because of its location, also has many former Big Three employees _ nearly a fourth of its workers. But <PERSON> Vladmir </PERSON> <PERSON> Pucik </PERSON>, international business professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION>, said the Japanese prefer `` a relatively inexperienced labor force so they can train them in the Japanese way of doing things. They want to go somewhere so nobody will say, ` At <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, we did it differently.'' <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON> conceded Chrysler-Mitsubishi sought fresh faces. `` We did n't want to have another car plant that -LRB- would -RRB- have 20 years of experience transferred to our plant,'' he said. `` We wanted some green people when it comes to building cars.'' But he said any suggestion race was involved in site selection was `` utter nonsense'' and any charge `` we selected a town to stay away from a union ... is absolutely and unequivocally dead wrong.'' The plant was built with a 100 percent unionized labor force. <LOCATION> Bloomington </LOCATION> Mayor Smart says the Japanese will be happy they built here. `` When you get into any rural setting, people are not afraid to put in long hours,'' he said. `` Here there's a satisfaction in seeing the end result. You're just bred that way.''
</TEXT>
