<FIRST>a a AM-Heartland-AutoFacts Adv23   01-13 0757</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Heartland-Auto Facts, Adv 23,0791</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, Jan. 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Statistics on U.S. and Japanese Auto Production</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Heartland-Motor Cities</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are some facts about the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> auto industry, the Japanese impact on it and black employment within it. The statistics are provided by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> union, the <ORGANIZATION> Wefa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> study by <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> Negrey </PERSON>, a study by <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> professors <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> and <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Deskins </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, and `` The State of <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>: 1988,'' a report published by <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> Executives.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Market Share: _ Japanese companies increased their share of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market from about 8 percent in 1976 to about 23 percent in 1987. _ An estimated 2.08 million Japanese imports and 737,513 `` transplants'' _ cars built totally or partly by the Japanese at <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sites _ were sold in this country last year. That accounted for 26.6 percent of the 10.52 million cars purchased in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Imports include cars such as the Dodge Colt, built by <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Transplants include products of joint U.S.-Japanese ventures, such as the Ford Probe, built by <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION>. _ The number of transplant autos built in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has risen steadily. The Wefa Group, an economic consulting organization, estimates Japanese transplants in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> will total 1.7 million cars in 1990, compared with 600,000 in 1986.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Imports: _ <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> exported 2.21 million cars to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the 1987 fiscal year, which ended last March. The Japanese government said shipments in the April-November period were 10.4 percent below those of a year earlier, but it still estimates <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> will have exported 2.2 million cars to this country when the current fiscal year ends in March. In 1981, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> imposed a voluntary export restraint in response to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> political pressure. It first limited annual exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to 1.68 million units. The cap was increased in steps to 2.3 million units in 1985. It has remained there since. Some Japanese automakers feel the quota is outdated because domestic car prices have become more attractive against the cost of Japanese cars, driven upward as the yen doubled in value over the last three years.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Exports: _ In 1986, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> produced 12.5 million vehicles and exported 40,000. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> produced 12.2 million vehicles, 6.6 million of which were exported.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Japanese Investment: _ In the 1980s, Japanese automakers have invested $ 5 billion in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assembly plants for cars and light trucks. _ Seven automakers and more than 100 auto parts suppliers with partial or total Japanese ownership are operating or building plants in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Since 1984, the number of Japanese-affiliated auto suppliers has nearly doubled in this country.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Job Loss: _ A 1988 <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report said Japanese-affiliated automakers could cause the loss of 45,000 jobs in the industry in 1990 if there was a high displacement rate -LRB- ` transplant' autos built in lieu of domestic cars -RRB-, a production level of 1.8 million vehicles by those companies and 50 percent of the cars' parts and materials were made in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> compared with 83 percent for traditional <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automakers. But the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> said the government underestimated the potential job loss due to transplants. The union said up to 74,000 jobs could be lost. _ The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> estimated a job loss of 360,000 from 1985 to 1990 from all factors, including transplants, gains in productivity, rising auto imports and increased use of foreign parts. However, the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> estimate was 470,000, noting Japanese-affiliated plants have built only a third of planned capacity. _ From 1985 to 1987, 169,000 auto manufacturing jobs have disappeared. That includes workers at the plants as well as those employed by industry suppliers.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Minorities: _ In 1984, according to reports filed with the <ORGANIZATION> Equal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opportunity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, blacks comprised 17.2 percent of all workers employed by the Big Three automakers and 8.4 percent of white-collar employees. Blacks make up nearly 11 percent of the civilian labor force. _ <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> estimated its 1987 payroll for its black employees was $ 3 billion. The March 1988 Current Population Survey estimated total 1987 wage and salary income for 12.9 million blacks was $ 178.8 billion. So, although <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s black workers represented just six-tenths percent of all black employees, they received 1.7 percent of the nation's black wage and salary income in 1987.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Jan. 23</NOTE>
