<HEAD>For Release Wed AMs, Jan 18, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: can survive.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> repeatedly told the story of the woman who bought an orange with her food stamps, then spent the change on a bottle of vodka. She could n't be found, either. Change from food stamps, incidentally, is limited to 99 cents. To illustrate the evils of school busing for racial balance, he had a tale about how the daughter of the very woman who brought the landmark 1954 school desegregation suit now had to be bused miles from her home to attend class. But <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, daughter of <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, went to school two blocks from her home in <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>. What's more, <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION> did n't have school busing for racial balance <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had lots of those. Remember the killer trees? Sometimes, he tripped over his own tongue as well as the facts. President <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Doe </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION> became `` Chairman <PERSON> Moe </PERSON>,'' and an open microphone caught him more than once in hip shots like `` All right, my fellow Americans, I am pleased to tell you today that I have signed legislation that will outlaw <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> forever. We begin bombing in five minutes.'' Not everybody thought these things funny, but <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, the Great Communicator, usually got away unscathed and unfazed. In part, doubtlessly, it was because he had such an infectious ability to disarm his critics by laughing at himself. And nobody deprecated <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> like <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. Before the Discovery launch last year, he was asked if he'd like to go into space. `` I've been there for several years,'' he deadpanned. That kind of humor and modesty went a long way to stir a nation's perception of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> as at once a normal man and a very special one <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> laughed with him, trusted him, admired his schoolboy optimism. And it forgave his indiscretions as family mischief. Educator and management consultant <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> wrote in `` Anatomy of Power,'' that `` great leaders, in bearing and behavior, make a distinction between authority and power,'' and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> `` never appears as an authority figure.'' Two other keys to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s success, <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> said, were his ability to communicate his sense of values, and his willingness to limit priorities. While <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> inundated <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the public, he noted, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> called forth one issue at a time, never scattering his shot. <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> was the last president to serve two full terms, but he left tired and with his successor, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, having campaigned on a promise `` to get <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> moving again.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> came along at a time when it appeared the national mood would hold any president to a single term. The presidency had been weakened by the overlapping traumas of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and Watergate, and, while <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON> and <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> restored the integrity of the office, the country remained wearied as it confronted the frustrations of an energy crisis, runaway inflation and the the hostage-taking of Americans in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, in an ill-advised speech that sounded his own political epitaph, complained of a national malaise, in which Americans suffered `` a crisis of confidence.'' By the time the voters turned him out after four years, <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> had aged 10. It seemed that way with <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, too. <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will be 78 on Feb. 6. But he looks and acts remarkably like the man who arrived in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> eight years ago, full of exuberance. His waistline may have expanded an inch, but not much more has swelled. He arrived with a size 7 hat. It still fits, and that's a major reason why the nation remains so fond of him.
