<SECOND>PM-Greenspan-Technology,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Technology's Effect On Economy Felt In Poorer Countries: Greenspan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> says the technological advances that have spurred changes in the world economy this decade are starting to be felt in poorer nations. Some heavily indebted nations _ for example, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> _ are beginning to show signs of economic vitality, <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said late Thursday in a speech at the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION>. `` We obviously still have very significant problems with the debtor nations and their economic structure.'' But <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said the nations are going through profound changes that make him optimistic that economic improvement may be forthcoming. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said that technological advances, which have `` downsized'' the goods produced by industrial nations and vastly improved communications, have put pressure on governments to open up their societies and economies. He said that `` perestroika,'' the name for Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s economic reform program, is a worldwide phenomenon and is evidence that centrally controlled economies as part of oppressive government leadership are becoming a thing of the past. `` If we could resolve the debt problem, which we're beginning to get some handle on, then I think we're going to find a really major renewal of economic capabilities in a number of these countries which have been under such terribly difficult pressure in recent years,'' he said.
</TEXT>
