<HEAD>Government Plans To Expand Imports To Hold Down Trade Surplus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The South Korean government has promised to expand its imports whenever the country's current account trade surplus exceeds quarterly targerts. Government officials said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was mostly likely to benefit from the plan, which was contained in an annual economic report presented to President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo Thursday. <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s trade surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was estimated at around $ 9 billion last year, down from nearly $ 10 billion in 1987. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s biggest market, taking about 35 percent of Korean exports which totaled $ 60.6 billion last year. The government said it will set up special task forces to remove various non-tariff barriers and prepare a schedule for opening the market for farm products.
</TEXT>
