<HEAD>Six Board Of Trade Members Get Fines, Suspensions In Wig Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Six traders have been suspended from conducting transactions at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> and fined thousands of dollars each for engaging in fraudulent practices. CBOT disciplinary authorities found all six had engaged in a scheme involving a trader who wore a wig and fake identification to conduct transactions, CBOT officials announced Thursday. The traders were linked through federal court testimony last summer to the wig scheme masterminded by veteran trader <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON>, who was sentenced in November to six years in prison. The disciplinary action, imposed Dec. 16 but announced this week, followed revelations by prosecutors in the Sanders probe. The suspensions ranged from 15 days to 10 years and fines were between $ 5,000 and $ 50,000 each. Investigators found all six engaged in `` fraud and dishonorable and dishonest conduct'' and `` reckless and unbusinesslike dealings inconsistent with just and equitable principles of trade.'' <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON>, 45, was found guilty of setting up the scheme in which <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Dewey </PERSON>, another former trader, donned a wig and used stolen trader badges and jackets to gain access to a restricted area near the Treasury Bond trading pit. The government claimed that because of the disguises, <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dewey </PERSON> and others in the scheme were able to claim $ 30,000 in trading profits without detection. <PERSON> Dewey </PERSON> was sentenced to five years in prison. The six suspended traders were identified as <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Schremser </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON>, <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Bratta </PERSON>, <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Bremner </PERSON>, <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutor </PERSON> and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinkade </PERSON>. Schremser and <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> testified under grants of immunity from prosecutors at <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON>' trial, the <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION> said. The CBOT board of governors levied the stiffest penalty against <PERSON> Bremner </PERSON>, who was suspended for 10 years, fined $ 50,000 and barred from associating with other members of the exchange during the suspension.
