 The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> has given a cool response to a proposal made by a group of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> congressmen to set up a bilateral panel to arbitrate trade disputes between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>. A spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s External Relations Commissioner <PERSON> Frans </PERSON> <PERSON> Andriessen </PERSON>, said Friday that the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> was `` reluctant'' about the plan. The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> was more interested in strengthening the procedures of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, the Geneva-based international trade body which normally arbitrates in trade disputes, he said. The spokesman, who asked not to be named, said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> congressmen had discussed the issue with <PERSON> Andriessen </PERSON> on Thursday in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>. He said that the congressmen suggested the panel could arbitrate in what they called `` relatively minor'' disputes such as the current quarrel about the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s ban on hormones in beef. In retaliation for the ban, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> imposed 100 percent tariffs affecting $ 100 million worth of trade in <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> goods. The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> will decide whether to take countermeasures at a meeting of its foreign ministers at the end of January.
