 The stock market was mixed today, faced with news of a smaller-than-expected rise in retail sales last month. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped .53 to 2,221.79 in the first half hour of trading. Gainers outnumbered losers by about 5 to 3 in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed issues, with 569 up, 344 down and 518 unchanged. Volume on the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> came to 21.60 million shares as of 10 a.m. on Wall Street. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported that retail sales increased 0.2 percent in December, a gain much smaller than most analysts had estimated. Stock traders seemed uncertain at first how to respond to the news. In the bond market, investors reacted positively, sending interest rates lower on the report's suggestion that economic activity was a bit less robust than had been thought. But the dollar declined in foreign exchange after the figures were made public. Brokers said blue-chip stocks also were faced with some selling to cash in on the gains that have recently carried the market to its highest levels since the October 1987 crash. Among actively traded blue chips, <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> was up -RRB- at 31 -RRB-; <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> held steady at 45, and <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> dropped \ to 122 ~ The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>'s composite index of all its listed common stocks rose .23 to 159.49. At the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the market value index was up .20 at 315.20. On Thursday the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average climbed 15.89 points to 2,222.32 _ less than 25 points shy of its close of 2,246.74 on Oct. 16, 1987, just before it took a 508-point drop on Black Monday. Advancing issues outnumbered declines by more than 3 to 2 on the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>, with 899 up, 569 down and 509 unchanged. <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> volume totaled 183 million shares, up from 148.95 million in the previous session.
