<HEAD>NTT To Release Traffic Information To Boost Fair Competition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s dominant phone company, under pressure from the government, said Friday it would disclose market information that would help its new long-distance competitors plan their strategies. <ORGANIZATION> Nippon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said it would reveal facts such as the number of calls made between administrative districts and the revenue from each district, as well as the number of phone subscribers in each city. The utility, long owned by the government, was privatized in 1985, and its telecommunications monopoly ended at the same time, but it held key traffic information as a corporate secret despite pressure from competitors and the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Posts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecommunications </ORGANIZATION>. `` The competition is getting quite severe for us in many different aspects, but we decided to disclose some of information we have to accommodate the needs of new common cariers,'' <ORGANIZATION> NTT </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Haruo </PERSON> <PERSON> Yamaguchi </PERSON> said at a news conference. <ORGANIZATION> NTT </ORGANIZATION> is the world's largest company in terms of its stock market valuation. The company has been disclosing the total number of subscribers nationwide, and the total number of calls made annually, but it withheld other details. Three companies, <ORGANIZATION> Teleway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> DDI </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecom </ORGANIZATION>, have started long-distance telephone services since 1986 in the 320-mile corridor between <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s two biggest cities, <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> NTT </ORGANIZATION> is reportedly losing its long-distance share to the three new common carriers. The <LOCATION> Tokyo-Osaka </LOCATION> corridor covers more than 70 percent of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s 120 million population, and the new companies are offering long-distance rates about 20 percent lower than <ORGANIZATION> NTT </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
