<FIRST>r f PM-China-Economy     01-13 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Economy,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Expects Unemployment to Jump by Half</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government today predicted that unemployment would rise from 2 percent to 3 percent as a result of an austerity plan designed to cut the economy's growth rate and reduce inflation. The announcement, the first of its kind, came as the government is struggling to cool an overheated economy that has boosted prices to record-high levels. People ran on banks last summer to take out their money and buy as much as possible before prices went higher still. `` The austerity measures will leave many people jobless,'' said <PERSON> Yuan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wu </PERSON>, spokeman for the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, or cabinet. `` The most seriously affected will be those in the construction industry, because it is those projects that we want to stop.'' He said the government hopes to cut inflation by 3 percent to 5 percent next year. He said anything lower would stifle economic developement. Yuan said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has an 18.5 percent rate of inflation, but some Chinese economists privately put it at about 40 percent. In a news conference summing up last year's economy, <PERSON> Yuan </PERSON> said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s gross national product in 1988 grew by 11.2 percent over 1987 to $ 368 billion. Industrial output led the surge, jumping by 17.7 percent. However, agriculture increased a disappointing 3 percent. Yuan said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> hopes to cut its gross national product to a 7.5 percent rate of growth this year. Under the plan, industrial production will fall to 8 percent growth and farm output will rise 4 percent. He said unemployment in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> was 2 percent and expected to rise 50 percent to 3 percent this year because of the government's austerity program Estimates by independent economists put the jobless figure much higher. The government imposed the austerity program in September to put the brakes on the price spiral that has eroded the standard of living for up to a fifth of city dwellers. A reform program designed to allow prices to float on the market was cut back severely. Under the austerity program, more than 10,000 projects have also been stopped, reducing investment by $ 9 billion, <PERSON> Yuan </PERSON> said. He said the government would move to cushion unemployment by guaranteeing the jobless a certain standard of living. He did not give details. Although most areas of the economy will be cut, the state will put more money into agriculture, <PERSON> Yuan </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> will increase its farm investment by $ 100 million, <ORGANIZATION> Yuan </ORGANIZATION> said. He said the austerity program has already slowed the growth of prices. In December, prices went up 26 percent over the same month the previous year. But, <PERSON> Yuan </PERSON> said the rate of increase was 0.8 percent less than in November. Bank deposits, another signal of economic activity, are again on the increase, he said. One of the reasons for the increase, however, is that many banks have frozen the assets of individually - and collectively-owned businesses Yuan also said a crackdown on corruption has returned $ 2.1 billion in embezzled funds to the state. More than 150 high-ranking officials from national companies have resigned and more than 30 big companies closed because of corruption inquiries, he said.
</TEXT>
