<HEAD>Bond Prices Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bond prices rose in early trading today, boosted by a government report showing lower-than-expected December retail sales and by a stronger dollar. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s benchmark 30-year bond rose 13-16 point, or about $ 8.12 per $ 1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction from its price, fell to 8.89 percent from 8.97 percent late Thursday. Retail sales were up 0.2 percent in December, less than the increase many analysts and economists had expected. The figure indicated that inflationary pressures may not be as great as believed; fear of inflation can lead to lower bond prices as investors flee the fixed-income market. The dollar also was up today in foreign-exchange trading despite reported sales of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency by central banks, providing further confidence for the bond market, analysts said. Another economic report released today, the December wholesale price index, was in line with the figure many experts expected, up 0.4 percent. In the secondary market for <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds, prices of short-term government issues rose from -LRB- point to 7-16 point, intermediate maturities were up 9-16 point and long-term issues were up from -RCB- point to 27-32 point, according to <ORGANIZATION> Telerate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a financial information service. The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $ 10 in the price of a bond with a $ 1,000 face value. The <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Bond Index, which measures price movements on all outstanding <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> issues with maturities of a year or longer, rose 4.63 to 1,136.30. In corporate trading, industrials were up. <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION>'s Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, rose 0.57 to 295.81. Yields on three-month <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills fell to 8.50 percent as the discount fell 5 basis points to 8.22 percent. Yields on six-month bills fell to 8.82 percent as the discount fell 5 basis points to 8.34 percent. Yields on one-year bills fell to 9.00 percent as the discount fell 5 basis points to 8.33 percent. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield is the annualized return on an investment in a <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bill. The discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face value, which is paid at maturity. The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, was quoted at 91-16 percent, unchanged from late Thursday.
