<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s carefully nurtured image of a family-style company where life is lovely and finances are fine is a smoke screen hiding serious flaws, says a former company executive's new book. `` I have written this book to say that the ` emperor has no clothes,' to expunge the illusion that <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> is OK,'' <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> says in explaining the reasoning behind `` <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION>: Debunking The Myth.'' `` Fact is Delta is not OK. Fact is Delta no longer deserves the reputation that it is financially impregnable and can endure and prosper in the worst of times. `` Fact is <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> is in need of strong medicine if it is to survive over the long term,'' writes <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, a former vice president and assistant general counsel, who quit in 1979 after 13 years at the airline and now serves as general counsel for an airplane leasing company in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. Industry analysts, however, see little to concern them at the Atlanta-based carrier, which generally enjoys a strong reputation on Wall Street and among the traveling public. `` No, I ca n't confess to be to worried about <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Decker </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Duff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Phelps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, an opinion echoed by <PERSON> Gail </PERSON> <PERSON> Scully </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> Argus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <