<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mexican oil prices rose an average of more than $ 2 a barrel in December in the wake of the new <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> quota agreement, the government oil monopoly <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION> said. The price of light Isthmus crude in the <LOCATION> Americas </LOCATION> was $ 13.93 a barrel in December, an increase from $ 11.62 in November, <ORGANIZATION> Petroleos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexicanos </ORGANIZATION> said late Thursday. The heavy Maya grade sold for $ 10.52 a barrel, compared with $ 9.21 a month earlier, and the extra-light Olmeca for $ 15.24, up from $ 12.90. Customers in the Far East paid $ 12.95 a barrel for Isthmus and $ 10.30 a barrel for Maya, increases from $ 10.82 and $ 8.22 a barrel respectively. Prices for European buyers during the first half of the month averaged $ 14.39 for Isthmus and $ 11.09 for Maya, up from $ 12.79 and $ 9.71. <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION> said the increases were the result of `` the significant recovery in prices of the principal crudes sold on the international petroleum market'' following the agreement Nov. 28 by the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> Exporting Countries. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s 13 members agreed to lower their output by nearly 4 million barrels a day, to 18.5 million barrels in an effort to stem the flow of excess oil and reverse the decline of world oil prices. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is not a member of <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>. Since the accord, prices for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, as well as <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and other crudes, have risen more than $ 3 a barrel. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s crude oil exports for 1988 averaged 1.3 million barrels a day and petrochemicals, 40,000 barrels a day, <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION> said. In December, 51.6 percent of crude oil exports went to the <LOC