<SECOND>AM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales Up Overall; GM Cars Down Substantially</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 U.S.-made car and truck sales rose 5.6 percent during early January this year compared with the same period last year, despite a 19.8 percent decline in car sales at <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, automakers said Friday. The drop at <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> may have been due to dealers moving some sales from early January to late December to inflate year-end numbers, analysts speculated. Strong truck sales helped bolster sagging automobile sales industrywide. The seven <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automakers said they sold cars and light trucks on a daily rate of 25,622 vehicles during the Jan. 1-10 period this year. During the same period last year, they sold cars and trucks at a daily rate of 24,252. There were seven selling days in both periods. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> was the only <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> maker to show a decline during the period, as its car sales skidded 19.8 percent, to a daily rate of 6,801 in early January this year compared with a rate of 8,481 during the same time last year. `` I think you're just seeing a payback from the end of December,'' said analyst <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Oppenheimer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` A few of the dealers probably called a few of the Jan. 3-4 sales Dec. 31 sales -LRB- to boost year-end figures -RRB-.'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> agreed, saying: `` Their sales were unbelievably good in late December and unbelievably bad in early January. If you add the two periods together and divide by two, things are about normal. `` There was a lot of year-end window dressing in late December,'' <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> added. During the final 10-day period of December, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> reported a daily sales rate of 14,657 cars a day, more than twice the early January rate. Overall, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automakers said they sold cars at a daily rate of 15,283 during the first 10 days of the year, a 3.1 percent decline from a daily rate of 15,765 during the same time last year. Car sales for <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> rose during early January, 13 percent and 11.4 percent, respectively. Light truck sales among all the makers rose 21.8 percent to a daily rate of 10,339 during early January this year compared with a rate of 8,488 last year. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s light truck sales showed a 46.9 percent increase in early January, climbing to a daily rate of 2,347 in 1989 from 1,598 during the period last year. Chrysler-made cars sold at a rate of 2,225 a day in early January this year, up from 1,998 daily rate of a year before. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said it sold trucks at a daily rate of 3,706 in early January, 23.8 percent more than the 2,993 early-January rate last year. Car sales at <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> rose to a daily rate of 5,346 in early January this year from a rate of 4,731 during the period last year. While its car sales rate fell, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s truck sales rose, going up 6.3 percent to a daily rate of 3,968 in early January of this year from a 3,732 truck-per-day rate during the same time last year.
