<HEAD>Copper Futures Advance On Chilean Refinery Blast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Copper futures prices rose sharply Friday on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in reaction to reports of a disastrous explosion at the smelting operations of the world's largest copper mine near <LOCATION> Chuquicamata </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>. On other markets, gold and silver futures retreated; coffee futures fell; grains and soybeans were mostly higher; energy, livestock and meat futures were mixed; and stock-index futures advanced. Copper settled 4.3 cents to 5.2 cents higher with the contract for delivery in March at $ 1.431 a pound. The <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s spot copper price settled at the day's high of $ 1.536 a pound The explosion of the flash furnace feeding <ORGANIZATION> Chilean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Copper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s Chuquicamata smelter was reported to have killed at least 16 people and could result in significant production losses, putting further strain on extremely tight copper supplies, analysts said `` The question of how much production loss will occur is not clear at all -LRB- but -RRB- any losses are very bullish because the market is so tight,'' said <PERSON> Bette </PERSON> <PERSON> Raptopoulos </PERSON>, a metal-market analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Production problems have plagued the worldwide copper industry in the past year, helping to drive the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s spot-month price to a record high of $ 1.6475 a pound on Dec. 8. A loss of production from <LOCATION> Chuquicamata </LOCATION> `` is not going to be a big supply problem in times to come but it will have an immediate short-term impact'' on prices, said analyst <ORGANIZATION> James </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Gold and silver futures prices fell moderately on the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, reflecting gains in the dollar's value against major foreign currencies, analysts said. Gold settled $ 2.30 to $ 2.40 lower with February at $ 403.50 a troy ounce; silver was 2.8 cents lower across the board with March at $ 5.957 a troy ounce. Coffee futures ended lower in a second day of volatile activity on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Coffee, <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Despite the decline, analysts said the market's bullish supply-and-demand fundamentals remained in place. Coffee settled 1.38 cents to 3.01 cents lower with March at $ 1.397 a pound. Grain and soybean futures ended mostly higher on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> ahead of an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> crop report that was released after the close of trading and is expected to boost wheat prices, and pressure corn and soybean prices, on Monday. In the report, the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> estimated 1989 winter-wheat seedings at 54.46 million acres, 12 percent above the 1988 tally but well below analysts' pre-report estimates. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> said 1988 soybean production totaled 1.54 billion bushels, 19.8 percent below the 1987 harvest but higher than most pre-report estimates and higher than the agency's Nov. 9 projection of 1.51 billion bushels. The government said 1988 corn production totaled 4.92 billion bushels, 30.3 percent below the 1987 harvest but much higher than pre-report estimates and the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s Nov. 9 projection of 4.67 billion bushels. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> pegged soybean stocks as of Dec. 1 at 1.37 billion bushels, compared with 1.76 billion bushels a year earlier; corn stocks at 7.07 billion bushels, compared with 9.77 billion bushels a year earlier; and wheat stocks at 1.71 billion bushels, compared with 2.51 billion bushels a year earlier. The soybean number was slightly below expectations while the wheat and corn figures were higher than expected. The winter-wheat seedings figure alone would have been `` very bullish'' for the wheat market, said <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON>, a trader with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. But he said buying enthusiasm in the wheat market on Monday probably would be tempered by the bearish corn and and soybean production numbers and the bearish wheat and corn stocks figures. The corn numbers were `` a shockingly bearish surprise,'' <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON> said, and could translate into opening declines of more than 5 cents a bushel on Monday. Wheat settled 1 -LCB- cents lower to -LCB- cent higher with March at $ 4.41 a bushel; corn was 2 \ cents to 3 cents higher with March at $ 2.88 \ a bushel; oats were 4 \ cents to 5 \ cents higher with March at $ 2.43 a bushel; soybeans were 1 \ cents to 6 \ cents higher with January at In energy futures trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Intermediate crude oil settled 14 cents lower to 31 cents higher with February at $ 18.48 a barrel; heating oil was .33 cent lower to .31 cent higher with February at 52.95 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .52 cent to 1.20 cents higher with February at 49.97 cents a gallon. Livestock and meat futures finished narrowly mixed on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .10 cent to .43 cent higher with February at 74.45 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .30 cent lower to .05 cent higher with January at 84.90 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent lower to .30 cent higher with February at 45.50 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .55 cent lower to .08 cent higher with February at 42.65 cents a pound. Stock-index futures advanced moderately on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where the contract for March delivery of stocks represented by the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500 index settled 1.05 points higher at 286.30. Each point is worth $ 500.
