<HEAD>Sundstrand May Pay Nearly $100 Million To Settle New Claims, Magazine
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKFORD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Sundstrand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> declined to comment Friday on a report that the aerospace contractor may pay the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> nearly $ 100 million to settle questionable billing practices. Quoting unidentified sources, Business Week magazine said the Pentagon is preparing an administrative settlement in which <ORGANIZATION> Sundstrand </ORGANIZATION> would make payments both in cash and contract-price guarantees to resolve the billing problem. `` We've made a standard practice not to comment on anything like that, which first of all we have n't seen and secondly it's an allegation on their part,'' <ORGANIZATION> Sundstrand </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Vernam </PERSON> said. The settlement would compound the effect of an unprecedented $ 127.3 million in fines levied against <ORGANIZATION> Sundstrand </ORGANIZATION> late last year after the company pleaded guilty to overcharging the Pentagon on defense contracts. In its Jan. 23 issue, Business Week reported that the administrative claim alleges the company billed the government for millions of dollars in costs unrelated to its Pentagon contracts. Sources also told the magazine that current or former <ORGANIZATION> Sundstrand </ORGANIZATION> executives may be indicted by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` Whether or not there will be any indictments and when those indictments would be handed down, we have no comment,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Clabault </PERSON>, one of several assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorneys working on the case. The federal prosecutor's office routinely declines comment on pending investigations. <ORGANIZATION> Sundstrand </ORGANIZATION> pleaded guilty Oct. 21 to four counts of defrauding the government by overbilling on aircraft parts. It also pleaded guilty in <LOCATION> Wa