<HEAD>Shearson To Report Fourth-Quarter Loss, Restate 1988 Profit</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: ADDS closing stock price in final graf; No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, Wall Street's largest firm, said Friday it would report a loss for the fourth quarter of 1988 due to bad investments in a troubled <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> bank The company also said it would revise downward its profit for the rest of 1988 because of previously reported accounting problems at <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary that caters to wealthy clients. <PERSON> Shearson </PERSON> did not estimate the amount of quarterly loss from devalued securities in MCorp of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, but said it would release fourth-quarter figures later this month. One stock analyst put the loss at $ 15 million to $ 16 million. With capital exceeding $ 4.5 billion, 40,000 employees and more than 700 offices worldwide, <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> i the largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investment firm. About 61 percent of it is owned by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the financial services giant. <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> said it will record a pretax charge of $ 70 million in the fourth quarter ended Dec. 30 to reflect a further reduction in the value of <ORGANIZATION> MCorp </ORGANIZATION> securities. Shearson initially lowered the value of the holdings in early 1988. To correct an overstatement in <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> earnings, <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> said it would restate profit for the first three quarters of 1988 that will lower <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>'s earnings for that period by $ 30 million, to about $ 110 million. <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON> said the problem at <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> stemmed from recording revenues that should have been deferred, and deferring expenses that should have been recorded. He said an unidentified employee disclosed the problem and there was no misuse of company or client assets. Last month, <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> estimated the restatement would result in a $ 15 million profit reduction. It also said three top <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> officers were suspended with pay over the improper accounting. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Schick </PERSON>, another <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said a committee of outside auditors and <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> officers is expected to determine who was responsible within a few weeks. <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> declined to name the three suspended officers. They have been identified by <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> newspapers as President <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Germeten </PERSON>, Executive Vice President <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> and Chief Financial Officer <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>. `` The review's conclusion was that what was involved here was accounting decisions that would boost the reported earnings,'' <PERSON> Schick </PERSON> said. `` In terms of what the motive was, I can not possibly speak to that. We do not believe that any laws were broken.'' <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> said it would have reported a fourth-quarter profit without the devaluation of MCorp holdings. <PERSON> Alison </PERSON> <PERSON> Deans </PERSON>, who follows the securities industry for <ORGANIZATION> Kidder </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, estimated the profit would have been $ 30 million to $ 35 million, or 30 to 35 cents a share Because of the MCorp problem, the loss should be $ 15 million to $ 16 million, she said. <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> said it owns <ORGANIZATION> MCorp </ORGANIZATION> money market cumulative prefered stock with a face value of $ 117.5 million, and <ORGANIZATION> MCorp </ORGANIZATION> subordinated debt securities with a principal amount of $ 29 million. After the adjustments, the preferred stock will be valued at $ 29.4 million and the debt securities at $ 11.6 million, <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> MCorp </ORGANIZATION>, which has requested financial assistance from the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, in October declared a moratorium on payment of preferred stock dividends and principal and interest on debt. Ms. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> acquired the <ORGANIZATION> MCorp </ORGANIZATION> securities after it agreed to underwrite them, or bring them to market, in early 1988. There was a lack of investor interest and <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> ending up buying them itself. It was unclear whether any other brokerage firms own MCorp securities in any significant amount. But Ms. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> said she did not foresee the fallout from the troubles in the banking and savings and loan industries becoming widespread in the securities industry. In composite <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading, <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>'s shares closed at $ 19.62 -LCB-, up 87 -LCB- cents from Thursday.
