<HEAD>Friday the 13th Economic News Helps Dollar, Stocks, Bonds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The government's Friday the 13th economic reports showing higher inflation and a mixed picture for retail sales did n't cast any bad-luck spells on the financial markets, where the dollar rallied, bond prices jumped and stocks reached the highest level since the Wall Street crash 15 months ago. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the rate of increase in wholesale prices nearly doubled in 1988 to 4 percent, the worst pace since the early 1980s. Although inflation remains far below the double-digit era of last decade, many economists expressed concern. `` I do n't like the sound of a doubling of inflation, but we have to put 4 percent in perspective,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> `` It's not that bad, but it's not that good either. In another report released Friday, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said retail sales in December rose a weak 0.2 percent, following strong increases in October and November. But for the year, retail spending rose 6.7 percent in 1988 to $ 1.61 trillion, the best performance in four years. The wholesale prices report had little effect on the markets, but some traders said the retail sales figure for December was weaker than expected and suggested that inflationary pressure was easing, which helped stocks and bonds. Others credited the strength in the markets to a relentless rise in the dollar's value despite coordinated dollar-selling by major central banks to stem the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency's advance. A more expensive dollar makes investments denominated in the currency more attractive. In the bond market, the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s benchmark 30-year bond rose nearly $ 10 per $ 1,000 in face value, while its yield declined from 8.97 percent late Thursday to 8.88 percent, the lowest in more than two months. Lower yields in the bond market encouraged investors to buy stocks and helped the market reach another in a recent series of post-crash highs. On Wall Street, the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average rose 3.75 points to 2,226.07, finishing the week with a net gain of 31.78 points.
